# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rachel-carson
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is one of the oldest and most widely available herbicides and defoliants in the world, having been commercially available since 1945, and is now produced by many chemical companies since the patent on it has long since expired.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] It can be found in numerous commercial lawn herbicide mixtures, and is widely used as a weedkiller on cereal crops, pastures, and orchards.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Over 1,500 herbicide products contain 2,4-D as an active ingredient.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D was first reported in 1944 by Franklin D.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The biological activity of 2,4-D as well as the similar hormone herbicides 2,4,5-T, and MCPA were discovered during World War II, a case of multiple discovery by four groups working independently under wartime secrecy in the United Kingdom and the United States: William G.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Templeman and associates at Imperial Chemical Industries (ICI) in the UK; Philip S.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Nutman and associates at Rothamsted Research in the UK; Franklin D.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Jones and associates at the American Chemical Paint Company; and Ezra Kraus, John W.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Mitchell, and associates at the University of Chicago and the United States Department of Agriculture.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] All four groups were subject to wartime secrecy laws and did not follow the usual procedures of publication and patent disclosure.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In December 1942, following a meeting at the Ministry of Agriculture the Rothamsted and ICI workers pooled resources and Nutman moved to Jealott's Hill to join the ICI effort.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The first scientific publication describing the 2,4-D structure and plant growth regulating activity was by Percy Zimmerman and Albert Hitchcock at the Boyce Thompson Institute, who were not the original inventors.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The precise sequence of early 2,4-D discovery events and publications has been discussed.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] William Templeman found that when indole-3-acetic acid (IAA), a naturally occurring auxin, was used at high concentrations, it could stop plant growth.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In 1940, he published his finding that IAA killed broadleaf plants within a cereal field.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] MCPA was discovered at about that time by his ICI group.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In the United States, a similar search for an acid with a longer half life, i.e., a metabolically and environmentally more stable compound, led to 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4-D) and 2,4,5-trichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4,5-T), both phenoxy herbicides and analogs of IAA.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Robert Pokorny, an industrial chemist for the C.B.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Dolge Company in Westport, Connecticut, published their synthesis in 1941.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D was not used as a chemical warfare agent during the war.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The Allies of World War II were looking for a chemical to starve Nazi Germany and Japan into submission by killing their potato and rice crops, but 2,4-D was found to be ineffective for that purpose, because both crops tolerate it.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Within a year after the war ended, 2,4-D was commercially released as an herbicide to control broadleaf weeds in grain crops such as rice and wheat, and in the 1950s it was registered in the United States to control size and enhance skin color in potatoes without affecting yields.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The first publication of 2,4-D's use as a selective herbicide came in 1944.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The ability of 2,4-D to control broadleaf weeds in turf was documented soon thereafter, in 1944.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Starting in 1945, the American Chemical Paint Company brought 2,4-D to market as an herbicide called "Weedone".
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] It revolutionized weed control, as it was the first compound that, at low doses, could selectively control dicotyledons (broadleaf plants), but not most monocotyledons — narrowleaf crops, such as wheat, maize (corn), rice, and similar cereal grass crops.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] At a time when labor was scarce and the need for increased food production was large, it literally "replaced the hoe".
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Its effectiveness, together with its non-corrosive, non-explosive and seemingly non-irritating or poisonous qualities, led to it being considered the best all-around herbicide by 1946.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is one of the ingredients in Agent Orange, an herbicide that was widely used during the Malayan Emergency and the Vietnam War.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] However, 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzodioxin (TCDD), a contaminant in the production of another ingredient in Agent Orange, 2,4,5-T, was the cause of the adverse health effects associated with Agent Orange.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In the 2000s, Dow AgroSciences developed a new choline salt version of 2,4-D (2,4-D choline) that Dow included in its "Enlist Duo" herbicide along with glyphosate and an agent that reduces drift; the choline salt form of 2,4-D is less volatile than 2,4-D.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is a member of the phenoxy family of herbicides.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] It is manufactured from chloroacetic acid and 2,4-dichlorophenol, which is itself produced by chlorination of phenol.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Alternatively, it is produced by the chlorination of phenoxyacetic acid.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The production processes may create several contaminants including di-, tri-, and tetrachlorodibenzo-*p*-dioxin isomers and *N*-nitrosamines, as well as monochlorophenol.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is a synthetic auxin that induces uncontrolled growth and eventually death in susceptible plants.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] It is absorbed through the leaves and is translocated to the meristems of the plant.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Uncontrolled, unsustainable growth ensues, causing stem curl-over, leaf withering, and eventual plant death.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is typically applied as an amine salt, but more potent ester versions exist, as well.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is primarily used as a selective herbicide that kills many terrestrial and aquatic broadleaf weeds, but not grasses.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D can be found in commercial lawn herbicide mixtures, which often contain other active ingredients including mecoprop and dicamba.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] A variety of sectors use products containing 2,4-D to kill weeds and unwanted vegetation.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In agriculture, it was the first herbicide for selective killing of weeds but not crops.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] It has been used since 1945 to control broad-leafed weeds in pastures, orchards, and cereal crops such as corn, oats, rice, and wheat.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Cereals, in particular, have excellent tolerance to 2,4-D when it is applied before planting.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is the cheapest way for farmers to control winter annual weeds by spraying in the fall, often at the lowest recommended rate.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] This is particularly effective before planting beans, peas, lentils, and chickpeas.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The estimated use of 2,4-D in US agriculture is mapped by the US Geological Survey.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In 2019, the latest date for which figures are available, this reached 45,000,000 pounds (20,000,000 kg) annually.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In domestic lawn and garden maintenance, 2,4-D is commonly used.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In forestry, it is used for stump treatment, trunk injection, and selective control of brush in conifer forests.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Along roadways, railways, and power lines, it is used to control weeds and brush which might interfere with safe operation and damage equipment.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Along waterways, it is used to control aquatic weeds that might interfere with boating, fishing, and swimming or clog irrigation and hydroelectric equipment.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] It is often used by government agencies to control the spread of invasive, noxious, and non-native weed species and prevent them from crowding out native species, and also to control many poisonous weeds such as poison ivy and poison oak.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D has been used in laboratories for plant research as a supplement in plant cell culture media such as MS medium since at least 1962.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is used in plant cell cultures as a dedifferentiation (callus induction) hormone.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] It is classified as an auxin plant hormone derivative.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Men who work with 2,4-D are at risk for abnormally shaped sperm and thus fertility problems; the risk depends on the amount and duration of exposure and other personal factors.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Environmental Protection Agency, "The toxicity of 2,4-D depends on its chemical forms, including salts, esters, and an acid form.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D generally has low toxicity for humans, except certain acid and salt forms can cause eye irritation.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Swimming is restricted for 24 hours after application of certain 2,4-D products applied to control aquatic weeds to avoid eye irritation." As of 2005 the median lethal dose or LD50 determined in acute toxicity rat studies was 639 mg/kg.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Urinary alkalinisation has been used in acute poisoning, but evidence to support its use is poor.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The International Agency for Research on Cancer classifies 2,4-D as a possible carcinogen to humans while the United States Environmental Protection Agency does not.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC), said 2,4-D was classified as "possibly carcinogenic to humans (Group 2B), based on inadequate evidence in humans and limited evidence in experimental animals".
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In June 2015 the World Health Organization's International Agency for Research on Cancer confirmed its 1987 classification of 2,4-D as a possible carcinogen.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] On August 8, 2007, the EPA issued a ruling that existing data do not support a link between human cancer and 2,4-D exposure.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] A 1995 panel of 13 scientists reviewing studies on the carcinogenicity of 2,4-D had divided opinions.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] None of the scientists thought the weight of the evidence indicated that 2,4-D was a "known" or "probable" cause of human cancer.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Two panelists believed it unlikely that 2,4-D can cause cancer in humans.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In a prior 1987 report the IARC classified some chlorphenoxy herbicides including 2,4-D, MCPA and 2,4,5-T as a group as class 2B carcinogens - "possibly carcinogenic to humans".
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D has been linked to lymphoma and bladder cancer in dogs.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] A July 2013 *Four Corners* investigation found elevated levels of dioxins in a generic version of 2,4-D, one of Australia's most widely used herbicides.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] When radioactively labeled 2,4-D was fed to livestock, 90% or more of the total radioactive residue (TRR) was shed in urine unchanged or as conjugated forms of 2,4-D.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] A relatively small portion of 2,4-D was metabolized into dichlorophenol, dichloroanisole, 4-chlorophenoxyacetic acid (6.9% of the TRR in milk), and 2,4-dichlorophenol (5% of the TRR in milk; 7.3% of the TRR in eggs and 4% of the TRR in chicken liver).
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Residue levels in kidney were the highest.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Owing to the longevity and extent of use, 2,4-D has been evaluated several times by regulators and review committees.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D amine salts and esters are not persistent under most environmental conditions.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The degradation of 2,4-D is rapid (half life of 6.2 days) in aerobic mineral soils.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is broken down by microbes in soil, in processes that involve hydroxylation, cleavage of the acid side-chain, decarboxylation, and ring opening.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The ethyl hexyl form of the compound is rapidly hydrolyzed in soil and water to form the 2,4-D acid.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D has a low binding affinity in mineral soils and sediment, and in those conditions is considered intermediately to highly mobile, and therefore likely to leach if not degraded.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In aerobic aquatic environments, the half life is 15 days.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In anaerobic aquatic environments 2,4-D is more persistent, with a half life of 41 to 333 days.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D has been detected in streams and shallow groundwater at low concentrations, in both rural and urban areas.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Some ester forms are highly toxic to fish and other aquatic life.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] "The ester forms of 2,4-D can be highly toxic to fish and other aquatic life.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D generally has moderate toxicity to birds and mammals, is slightly toxic to fish and aquatic invertebrates, and is practically nontoxic to honeybees" per EPA.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] A number of 2,4-D-degrading bacteria have been isolated and characterized from a variety of environmental habitats.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Metabolic pathways for the compound's degradation have been available for many years, and genes encoding 2,4-D catabolism have been identified for several organisms.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] As a result of the extensive metadata on environmental behavior, physiology, and genetics, 2,4-D was the first herbicide for which the bacteria actively responsible for *in situ*degradation were demonstrated.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] This was accomplished using the technique of DNA-based stable isotope probing, which enables a microbial function (activity), such as degrading a chemical, to be linked with the organism's identity without the need to culture the organism involved.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Maximum residue limits were first set in the EU in 2002 and re-evaluated in 2011 by the European Food Safety Authority, which concluded that the codex maximum residue limits were "not expected to be of concern for European consumers".
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The total chronic exposure represented less than 10% of the acceptable daily intake (ADI).
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D is currently not approved for use on lawns and gardens in Denmark, Norway, Kuwait, and the Canadian provinces of Québec and Ontario.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] 2,4-D use is severely restricted in the country of Belize.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In 2008, Dow AgroScience, LLC, sued the Canadian government for allowing Quebec to ban 2,4-D, but settled in 2011.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In 2012, EPA denied the petition filed November 6, 2008, by the Natural Resources Defense Council to revoke all tolerances and to cancel all registrations of 2,4-D.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] EPA stated that new study and EPA's comprehensive review confirmed EPA's previous finding that the 2,4-D tolerances are safe at anticipated exposure.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] The estimated annual use of 2,4-D in US agriculture is mapped by the US Geological Service.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In October 2014, the US EPA registered Enlist Duo, an herbicide containing the less volatile 2,4-D choline salt, glyphosate, and an antidrift agent, for use in six states: Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Ohio, South Dakota, and Wisconsin.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In November 2015, the EPA attempted to withdraw its own approval of Enlist Duo, as a result of legal actions against both the agency and Dow by two U.S. groups.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] However, while it was implied that the approval was "gone" because of the action, in fact, Enlist Duo was still approved pending a decision by the courts.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] On January 25, 2016, the US Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals denied EPA's motion to vacate its Enlist Duo registration.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Dow stated the product would be available in 15 US states and Canada for the 2016 crop season.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] On August 21, 2013, the Australian Pesticides and Veterinary Medicines Authority (APVMA) banned selected 2,4-D high volatile ester (HVE) products due to their environmental hazards.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] HVE 2,4-D products had already been banned in Europe and North America for 20 years; low volatile ester products continue to be available in Australia and worldwide.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In July 2013 APVMA published their report findings.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In 2010, Dow published that it had created genetically modified soybeans made resistant to 2,4-D by insertion of a bacterial aryloxyalkanoate dioxygenase gene, *aad1*.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] Dow intended it to be used as an alternative or complement to Roundup Ready crops due to the increasing prevalence of glyphosate-resistant weeds.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] As of April 2014, genetically modified maize and soybeans resistant to 2,4-D and glyphosate have been approved in Canada.
[src:rachel-carson/2-4-dichlorophenoxyacetic-acid] In September 2014, the USDA also approved Dow's maize and soybeans, and in October, the EPA registered the "Enlist Duo" herbicide containing 2,4-D and glyphosate.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] 3-AT is a competitive inhibitor of the product of the HIS3 gene, imidazoleglycerol-phosphate dehydratase.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] Imidazoleglycerol-phosphate dehydratase is an enzyme catalyzing the sixth step of histidine production.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] 3-AT is also a nonselective systemic triazole herbicide used on nonfood croplands to control annual grasses and broadleaf and aquatic weeds.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] It is not used on food crops because of its carcinogenic properties.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] As an herbicide, it is known as *aminotriazole*, *amitrole* or *amitrol*.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] Amitrol was included in a biocide ban proposed by the Swedish Chemicals Agency and approved by the European Parliament on January 13, 2009.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] Amitrol's mode of action is unknown, though it is classed as a resistance group Q herbicide.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] By applying 3-AT to a yeast cell culture which is dependent upon a plasmid containing HIS3 to produce histidine (i.e. its own HIS3 analogue is not present or nonfunctional), an increased level of HIS3 expression is required in order for the yeast cell to survive.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] This has proved useful in various two-hybrid system, where a high-affinity binding between two proteins (i.e., higher expression of the HIS3 gene) will allow the yeast cell to survive in media containing higher concentrations of 3-AT.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] This selection process is performed using selective media, containing no histidine.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] On November 9, 1959, the secretary of the United States Department of Health, Education, and Welfare, Arthur S.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] Flemming, announced that some of the 1959 cranberry crop was tainted with traces of the herbicide aminotriazole.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] The market for cranberries collapsed and growers lost millions of dollars.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] However, Ocean Spray recovered by expanding the market for cranberry juice, which, although widely available for sale, was before then not popular.
[src:rachel-carson/3-amino-1-2-4-triazole] This ensured cranberry growers would not have to rely mostly on Thanksgiving and Christmas for sales, which was the case until the 1959 incident.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Her former home of Liberty Farm in Worcester, Massachusetts, has been designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] On January 15, 1811, Abigail (Abby) Kelley was born the seventh daughter of Wing and Lydia Kelley, farmers in Pelham, Massachusetts.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley grew up helping with the family farms in Worcester where she received a loving, yet strict Quaker upbringing.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley and her family were members of the Quaker Meeting in nearby Uxbridge, Massachusetts.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She began her education in a single-room schoolhouse in the Tatnuck section of Worcester.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] After her first year of school, Kelley taught for two years to make enough money to further her education.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In 1829, she attended her final year of schooling, having received the highest form of education any New England woman of her relatively moderate economic standing could hope to obtain.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Abby returned to her parents' home to teach in local schools and, in 1835, helped her parents move to their new home in Millbury.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Then in 1836, she moved to Lynn, Massachusetts, where she taught at a local school.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] There she met fellow Quakers who preached the ideas of dietary restriction, temperance, pacifism, and antislavery.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She became interested in the health theories of Sylvester Graham and gained a general interest in the abolition of slavery after hearing a lecture by William Lloyd Garrison, editor of the abolitionist publication *The Liberator*.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley joined the Female Anti-Slavery Society of Lynn and was soon elected to a committee charged with collecting signatures for petitions to the Federal government to end slavery in the District of Columbia.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley passionately carried out her assignment, and in 1837 collected the signatures of nearly half the women of Lynn.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley's views became progressively more radical as she worked with abolitionists such as Angelina Grimké.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She became an "ultra", advocating not only the abolition of slavery but also full civil equality for black people.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In addition, Garrison's influence led her to adopt the position of "non-resistance", which went beyond opposing war to opposing all forms of government coercion.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Radical abolitionists led by Garrison refused to serve on juries, join the military or vote.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] The Garrisonian call for the end of slavery and the extension of civil rights to African Americans caused controversy.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley's advocacy of the radical abolitionist movement prompted some opponents to call her a "Jezebel", as what she proposed threatened their sense of social structure.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] On the other hand, many fellow abolitionists praised her public speaking skills and her dedication to the cause.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley's influence was shown by activist women being called "Abby Kelleyites".
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Following the financial Panic of 1837, Kelley took charge of fundraising for the Lynn Female Society.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She donated a generous portion of her own money to the American Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] With the encouragement of Angelina Grimke, Abby served as the Lynn Female Society's first delegate to the national convention of the Anti-Slavery Society in New York.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] There she spoke out about fundraising and participated in drafting the Society's declaration for abolition.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] After the convention, Kelley became even more engaged in the Anti-Slavery Society, for which she distributed petitions, raised funds, and participated in conferences to raise public awareness.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In 1838, Kelley gave her first public speech to a "promiscuous" (mixed-gender) audience at the first Anti-Slavery Convention of American Women, in Philadelphia.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] At this time women generally did not address such audiences in public forums.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Despite vociferous protesters, Kelley eloquently proclaimed the doctrine of abolitionism.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In the following months, she further established herself as a public figure by speaking to more mixed-gender crowds, such as that at the New England Anti-Slavery Convention.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She also worked on a committee composed of both genders.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Later in 1838, she moved to Connecticut to spread the anti-slavery message.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] By 1839, Kelley was fully involved in the Anti-Slavery Society, while still acknowledging Quaker tradition by refusing payment for her efforts.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In 1841, however, she resigned from the Quakers over disputes about not allowing anti-slavery speakers in meeting houses (including the Uxbridge monthly meeting where she had attended with her family), and the group disowned her.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In 1843, Kelley addressed the attendees at the Liberty Party convention in Buffalo, New York, becoming the first woman in America to speak at a national political convention.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In the following years, Kelley contributed to the Anti-Slavery Society as a lecturer and fundraiser.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Although she encountered constant objections to her public activism as a woman working closely with and presenting public lectures to men, Kelley continued her work.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She often shared her platform with formerly enslaved Africans despite disapproval by some in the audience.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] "I rejoice to be identified with the despised people of color.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] If they are to be despised, so ought their advocates to be".
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In October 1849, Kelley wrote to her friend, Milo Townsend, and told of the work she was doing for the anti-slavery society: "We know our cause is steadily onward".
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Some male members of the Society objected to the ideas propounded by Garrison, Kelley, and other radicals.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] As a result, when Kelley was elected to the national business committee of the Anti-Slavery Society, conservative members left in protest.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] The two groups of abolitionists officially severed.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Pacifist radical abolitionists controlled the Society, who promoted complete egalitarianism, to be obtained without the aid of any government, as all such institutions were constructed on the violence of war.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In 1854 Kelley became the Anti-Slavery Society's chief fundraiser and general financial agent, and in 1857 she took the position of general agent in charge of lecture and convention schedules.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley and her husband Stephen Symonds Foster – along with Sojourner Truth, Jonathan Walker, Marius Robinson, and Sallie Holley – reorganized the Michigan Anti-Slavery Society in 1853 in Adrian, Michigan.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] The state society was founded in 1836 in Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Fighting for women's rights soon became a new priority for many ultra abolitionists and Kelley was among them.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She spoke on women's rights in Seneca Falls, New York, five years before the Seneca Falls Convention would be held there.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley influenced future suffragists such as Susan B.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Anthony and Lucy Stone by encouraging them to take on a role in political activism.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She helped organize and was a key speaker at the first National Women's Rights Convention in Worcester, Massachusetts, in 1850.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] (The Seneca Falls Convention, the first women's rights convention, held in 1848, was not national).
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] After the American Civil War, Kelley supported passage of the 15th Amendment to the Constitution.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Some female activists resisted any amendment that did not include women's suffrage.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Anthony and Elizabeth Cady Stanton due to their strong opposition to the amendment.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] After the amendment passed and Garrison dissolved the Anti-Slavery Society, Kelley continued to work for equal rights for both African Americans and women.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In 1872, Kelley and her husband Stephen Symonds Foster refused to pay taxes on their jointly owned property; they argued that as Kelley could not vote, she was a victim of taxation without representation.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Although their farm was consequently seized and sold and repurchased for them by friends, Kelley continued her activism in the face of financial difficulties and poor health.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She wrote letters to fellow radicals and other political figures until her death in 1887.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] After a four-year courtship, Kelley married fellow abolitionist Stephen Symonds Foster in 1845.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In 1847, she and her husband purchased a farm in the Tatnuck region of Worcester, Massachusetts, and named it "Liberty Farm".
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She gave birth to their only daughter in 1847.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] The farm served both as a stop on the Underground Railroad and as a refuge for fellow reformers.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Kelley continued her efforts as a lecturer and fundraiser throughout the North until 1850, when declining health forced her to reduce traveling.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] She carried on an active correspondence and local meetings to work for the cause.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Abby Kelley Foster died January 14, 1887, one day before her 76th birthday.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Liberty Farm in Worcester, Massachusetts, the home of Abby Kelley and Stephen Symonds Foster, was designated a National Historic Landmark because of its association with their lives of working for abolitionism.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] It is privately owned and not open for visits.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Abby's House, a shelter for women that opened in Worcester in 1976, is named in her honor.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] In 2011, she was inducted into the National Women's Hall of Fame. she was also inducted in 2011 to the National Abolition Hall of Fame.
[src:rachel-carson/abby-kelley-foster] Abby Kelley Foster Charter Public School, a K-12 school in Worcester, Massachusetts, that opened in 1998, is named in her honor.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams's life is one of the most documented of the first ladies.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Many of the letters she wrote to John Adams while he was in Philadelphia as a delegate in the Continental Congress, prior to and during the Revolutionary War, document the closeness and versatility of their relationship.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] John Adams frequently sought the advice of Abigail on many matters, and their letters are filled with intellectual discussions on government and politics.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Her letters also serve as eyewitness accounts of the home front of the Revolutionary War.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Surveys of historians conducted periodically by the Siena College Research Institute since 1982 have consistently found Adams to rank as one of the three most highly regarded first ladies by historians.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail Adams was born on November 22, 1744, at the North Parish Congregational Church in Weymouth, Massachusetts, to William Smith and Elizabeth (née Quincy) Smith.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] On her mother's side, she was descended from the Quincy political family, a well-known political family in the Massachusetts colony.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Through her mother she was a cousin of Dorothy Quincy, who was married to John Hancock.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams was also the great-granddaughter of John Norton, founding pastor of Old Ship Church in Hingham, Massachusetts, the only remaining 17th-century Puritan meetinghouse in Massachusetts.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Smith married Elizabeth Quincy in 1740, and together they had three daughters and a son; Abigail was the second child.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] As with several of her ancestors, Adams's father was a liberal Congregational minister: a leader in a Yankee society that held its clergy in high esteem.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Smith did not focus his preaching on predestination or original sin; instead he emphasized the importance of reason and morality.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In October 1775 his wife Elizabeth, with whom he had been married for 35 years, died.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] The Smith family were slaveholders and are known to have owned at least four people.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] A slave named Phoebe took a caretaking role to Abigail and other children; later on she would work as a paid servant for Abigail after she became free.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail would come to express anti-slavery beliefs as an adult.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail did not receive formal schooling; she was frequently sick as a child, something which may have been a factor preventing her from receiving an education.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Later in life, Adams would also consider that she was deprived an education because females were rarely given such an opportunity.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Although she did not receive a formal education, her mother taught her and her sisters to read, write and cipher; her father's, uncle's and grandfather's large libraries enabled the sisters to study English and French literature.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Her grandmother, Elizabeth Quincy, also contributed to Adams's education.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] As she grew up, Adams read with friends in an effort to further her learning.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She became regarded as one of the most erudite women ever to serve as first lady.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail Smith first met John Adams when she was 15 years old in 1759.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] John accompanied his friend Richard Cranch to the Smith household.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Cranch was engaged to Abigail's older sister, Mary Smith, and they would be the parents of federal judge William Cranch.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Although Abigail's father approved of the match, her mother was appalled that her daughter would marry a country lawyer whose manner still reeked of the farm.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Eventually, she gave in, and the couple married on October 25, 1764, in the Smiths' home in Weymouth.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] William Smith, Abigail's father, presided over the marriage.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] After the reception, the couple mounted a single horse and rode off to their new home, the saltbox house and farm John had inherited from his father in Braintree, Massachusetts (a location that is now part of Quincy).
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] The couple welcomed their first child nine months into their marriage.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Her childrearing style included relentless and continual reminders of what the children owed to virtue and the Adams tradition.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams was responsible for family and farm when her husband was on his long trips.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] "Alas!", she wrote in December 1773, "How many snow banks divide thee and me." Abigail and John's marriage is well documented through their correspondence and other writings.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Letters exchanged throughout John's political obligations indicate his trust in Abigail's knowledge was sincere.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Like her husband, Abigail often quoted literature in her letters.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Historian David McCullough claims that she did so "more readily" than her husband.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Their correspondence illuminated their mutual emotional and intellectual respect.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] John often excused himself to Abigail for his "vanity", exposing his need for her approval.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] John Adams moved the family to Boston in April 1768, renting a clapboard house on Brattle Street that was known locally as the "White House".
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] He and Abigail and the children lived there for a year, then moved to Cold Lane; still later, they moved again to a larger house in Brattle Square in the center of the city.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] John's growing law practice required changes for the family.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In 1771, he moved Abigail and the children back to Braintree, but he kept his office in Boston, hoping the time away from his family would allow him to focus on his work.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Nevertheless, after some time in the capital, he became disenchanted with the rural and "vulgar" Braintree as a home for his family, and thus, in August 1772, Adams moved his family back to Boston.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] He purchased a large brick house on Queen Street, not far from his office.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In 1774, Abigail and John returned the family to the farm due to the increasingly unstable situation in Boston, and Braintree remained their permanent Massachusetts home.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail also took responsibility for the family's financial matters, including investments.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Her investments made through her uncle Cotton Tufts in debt instruments issued to finance the Revolutionary War were rewarded after Alexander Hamilton's First Report on the Public Credit endorsed full federal payment at face value to holders of government securities.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] One recent researcher even credits Abigail's financial acumen with providing for the Adams family's wealth through the end of John's lifetime.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In 1784, Abigail and her daughter Nabby joined her husband and her eldest son, John Quincy, at her husband's diplomatic post in Paris.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail had dreaded the thought of the long sea voyage, but in fact found the journey interesting.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] At first, she found life in Paris difficult and was rather overwhelmed by the novel experience of running a large house with a retinue of servants.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] After 1785, she filled the role of wife of the first U.S. minister to the Court of St James's (Britain).
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In contrast to Paris, Abigail disliked London, where she had few friends and was, in general, cold-shouldered by polite society.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] One pleasant experience was her temporary guardianship of Thomas Jefferson's young daughter Mary (Polly), for whom Abigail came to feel a deep and lifelong love.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She and John returned in 1788 to their home in Quincy, Peacefield (also known as the "Old House"), which she set about vigorously enlarging and remodeling.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] It still stands and is open to the public as part of Adams National Historical Park.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] John Adams was inaugurated as the second president of the United States on March 4, 1797, in Philadelphia at the age of 61.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail was not present at her husband's inauguration as she was tending to his dying 89-year-old mother.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] When John was elected President of the United States, Abigail continued a formal pattern of entertaining.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She held a large dinner each week, made frequent public appearances, and provided for entertainment for the city of Philadelphia each Fourth of July.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She took an active role in politics and policy, unlike the quiet presence of Martha Washington.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail was so politically active, her political opponents came to refer to her as "Mrs.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] As John's confidant, Abigail was often well informed on issues facing her husband's administration, at times including details of current events not yet known to the public in letters to her sister Mary and her son John Quincy.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Some people used Abigail to contact the president.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] At times Abigail planted favorable stories about her husband in the press.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail remained a staunch supporter of her husband's political career, supporting his policies, such as passing the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams brought the children of her brother William Smith, her brother-in-law John Shaw, and her son Charles to live in the President's House during her husband's presidency because the children's fathers all struggled with alcoholism.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Charles's daughter, Susanna, was just 3 years old in 1800 when Adams brought her to live in the President's House in Philadelphia days before Charles's death.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] With the relocation of the capital to Washington, D.C. in 1800, she became the first First Lady to reside at the White House, or President's House as it was then known.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams moved into the White House in November 1800, living there for only the last four months of her husband's term.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] At this time, the city of Washington D.C. was wilderness, with the President's House far from completion.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She found the unfinished mansion in Washington "habitable" and the location "beautiful"; but she complained that, despite the thick woods nearby, she could find no one willing to chop and haul firewood for the First Family.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail used the East Room of the White House to hang up the laundry.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams's health, never robust, suffered in Washington.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] After John's defeat in his presidential re-election campaign, the family retired to Peacefield in Quincy in 1800.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail followed her son's political career earnestly, as her letters to her contemporaries show.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She continued to raise her granddaughter Susanna.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She also raised her elder grandchildren, including George Washington Adams and a younger John Adams, while their father John Quincy Adams was minister to Russia.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams's 48-year-old daughter, Nabby, died of breast cancer in 1813, after having endured three years of severe pain.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail Adams became ill during her final years.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She died in her home on October 28, 1818, of typhoid fever.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She was buried in what was to become the family crypt, which now also holds her husband John, their son John Quincy, and John Quincy's wife Louisa, located in the United First Parish Church (also known as the "Church of the Presidents") in Quincy, Massachusetts.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She was 73 years old, exactly two weeks shy of her 74th birthday.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Her last words were, "Do not grieve, my friend, my dearest friend.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] And John, it will not be long." Less than eight years later, on July 4, 1826, the fiftieth anniversary of the Declaration of Independence, her husband died of heart failure at the age of 90.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] He was buried next to her in the family crypt in the United First Parish Church.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Biographer Lynne Withey argues for her conservatism because she: "feared revolution; she valued stability, believed that family and religion were the essential props of social order, and considered inequality a social necessity".
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Despite believing firmly in women's domestic role, Abigail Adams advocated for women's rights in her letters to John Adams without reservation.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Furthermore, Abigail Adams was a firm believer that women are as qualified for political positions as men.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Her letters demonstrate the belief that women have a mind just like men and should have a voice in politics.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail did not make comments about women in passing; rather, she understood the social standing and value of women and believed that by writing letters about her experiences, she was raising awareness for other women.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Abigail Adams wrote about the troubles and concerns she had as an 18th-century woman.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She was an advocate of married women's property rights and more opportunities for women, particularly in the field of education.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She is known for her March 1776 letter to John and the Continental Congress, requesting that they, "remember the ladies, and be more generous and favorable to them than your ancestors.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Do not put such unlimited power into the hands of the Husbands.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Remember all Men would be tyrants if they could.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams opposed the existence of slavery in the United States and saw it as a threat to American democracy.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In a letter she wrote on March 31, 1776, Adams doubted that the majority of White people in Virginia had such "passion for Liberty" as they claimed they did, since they "deprive[d] their fellow Creatures" of freedom.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] One incident regarding Adams's views on race happened in Philadelphia in 1791, when a free black youth came to her house asking to be taught how to read and write.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams subsequently placed the boy in a local evening school, though not without objections from a neighbor.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams responded that he was "a Freeman as much as any of the young Men and merely because his face is black, is he to be denied instruction?
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] How is he to be qualified to procure a livelihood? ...
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams was an active member of First Parish Church in Quincy, which became Unitarian in doctrine by 1753.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Her theological views evolved over the course of her life.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Ellis argues that Abigail was the more resilient and more emotionally balanced of the two, and calls her one of the most extraordinary women in American history.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] The Abigail Adams Cairn – a mound of rough stones – crowns the nearby Penn Hill from which she and her son, John Quincy Adams, watched the Battle of Bunker Hill and the burning of Charlestown.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] At that time she was minding the children of Dr.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Joseph Warren, president of the Massachusetts Provincial Congress, who was killed in the battle.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] One of the subpeaks of New Hampshire's Mount Adams (whose main peak is named for her husband) is named in her honor.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In 2003, Adams was one of three women honored in a bronze sculpture as part of the Boston's Women Memorial on the Commonwealth Avenue Mall in Boston.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In 2022, a seven-foot tall bronze statue of Adams was unveiled in Quincy, Massachusetts, on the Hancock Adams Common.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] An Adams Memorial has been proposed in Washington, D.C., honoring Adams, her husband, her son, and other members of their family.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Passages from Adams's letters to her husband figured prominently in songs from the Broadway musical *1776*.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Virginia Vestoff played Adams in the original 1969 Broadway production of *1776* and recreated the role for the film version in 1972.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] On television, Kathryn Walker and Leora Dana portrayed Adams in the 1976 PBS mini-series *The Adams Chronicles*.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In the mini-series *John Adams*, which premiered in March 2008 on HBO, she was played by Laura Linney.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Adams is a featured figure on Judy Chicago's installation piece *The Dinner Party*, being represented as one of the 999 names on the *Heritage Floor*.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Novelist Barbara Hambly, writing as Barbara Hamilton, wrote three historical mysteries set in the early 1770s told from Abigail Adams's perspective (and featuring Abigail as the detective): *The Ninth Daughter* (2009), *A Marked Man* (2010), and *Sup with the Devil* (2011).
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] The First Spouse Program under the Presidential $1 Coin Program authorizes the United States Mint to issue half-ounce $10 gold coins and bronze medal duplicates to honor the first spouses of the United States.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] The Abigail Adams coin was released on June 19, 2007, and sold out in just hours.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] She is pictured on the back of the coin writing her most famous letter to John Adams.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In February 2009 *Coin World* reported that some 2007 Abigail Adams medals were struck using the reverse from the 2008 Louisa Adams medal, apparently by mistake.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] These pieces, called mules, were contained within the 2007 First Spouse medal set.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Mint has not released an estimate of how many mules were made.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] Consistently, Adams has ranked among the three-most highly regarded first ladies in these surveys.
[src:rachel-carson/abigail-adams] In the 2014 survey, Adams and her husband were ranked the 5th-highest out of 39 first couples in terms of being a "power couple".
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] The **Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature Film** is an award for documentary films.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] In 1941, the first awards for feature-length documentaries were bestowed as Special Awards to *Kukan* and *Target for Tonight*.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] They have since been bestowed competitively each year, with the exception of 1946.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Copies of every winning film (along with copies of most nominees) are held by the Academy Film Archive.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Following the Academy's practice, films are listed below by the award year (that is, the year they were released under the Academy's rules for eligibility).
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] In practice, due to the limited nature of documentary distribution, a film may be released in different years in different venues, sometimes years after production is complete.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Finalists for Best Documentary Feature are selected by the Documentary Branch based on a preliminary ballot.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] A second preferential ballot determines the five nominees.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Prior to the 78th Academy Awards, there were twelve films shortlisted.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Michael Moore's *Fahrenheit 9/11*, at the time the highest-grossing documentary film in movie history, was ruled ineligible because Moore had opted to have it played on television prior to the 2004 election.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Previously, the 1982 winner *Just Another Missing Kid* had already been broadcast in Canada and won that country's ACTRA award for excellence in television at the time of its nomination.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] In 1990, a group of 45 filmmakers filed a protest to the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences over a potential conflict of interest involving Mitchell Block.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] They noted that Michael Moore's *Roger & Me* (distributed by Warner Brothers) was omitted from the nominees, although it had been highly praised by numerous critics and was ranked by many critics as one of the top ten films of the year.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] The controversy over *Hoop Dreams*' exclusion was enough to have the Academy Awards begin the process to change its documentary voting system.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Roger Ebert, who had declared it to be the best 1994 movie of any kind, looked into its failure to receive a nomination: "We learned, through very reliable sources, that the members of the committee had a system.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] When one gave up on a film, he waved a light on the screen.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] When a majority of flashlights had voted, the film was switched off.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] The Academy's executive director, Bruce Davis, took the unprecedented step of asking accounting firm Price Waterhouse to turn over the complete results of that year's voting, in which members of the committee had rated each of the 63 eligible documentaries on a scale of six to ten.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] "What I found," said Davis, "is that a small group of members gave zeros (actually low scores) to every single film except the five they wanted to see nominated.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] And they gave tens to those five, which completely skewed the voting.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] There was one film that received more scores of ten than any other, but it wasn't nominated.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] In 2000, Arthur Cohn, the producer of the winning *One Day in September* boasted "I won this without showing it in a single theater!" Cohn had hit upon the tactic of showing his Oscar entries at invitation-only screenings, and to as few other people as possible.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Oscar bylaws at the time required voters to have seen all five nominated documentaries; by limiting his audience, Cohn shrank the voting pool and improved his odds.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Following protests by many documentarians, the nominating system was subsequently changed.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] The awards process has also been criticized for emphasizing a documentary's subject matter over its style or quality.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] In 2014, following the announcement of the shortlist of eligible feature documentary nominees, Sony Pictures Classics co-president Tom Bernard publicly criticized Academy documentary voters after they excluded SPC's *Red Army* from the shortlist.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] "It's a sign of some really old people in the documentary area of the Academy.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] There's a lot of people who are really up in their years.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] It's shocking to me that that film (*Red Army*) didn't get in," Bernard said.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Additionally, in his reporting of the Oscar documentary shortlist exclusions that year, *The Hollywood Reporter*'s Scott Feinberg reacted to *Red Army*'s omission: "...no matter which 15 titles the doc branch selected, plenty of other great ones would be left on the outside.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] That is the case, most egregiously, with Gabe Polsky's *Red Army* (Sony Classics), a masterful look at the role of sports in society and Russian-American relations".
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] In 2017, following the win of the eight-hour *O.J.: Made in America* in this category, the Academy announced that multi-part and limited series would be ineligible for the award in the future, even if they are not broadcast after their Oscar-qualifying release (as was *O.J.: Made in America*).
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Though Academy rules do not expressly preclude documentaries from being nominated in other competitive categories, documentaries are typically considered ineligible for nominations in categories that presume the work is fictitious, including Best Production Design, Best Costume Design, and acting.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] To date, no documentaries have been nominated for Best Picture, or Best Director.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] *The Quiet One* was nominated for Best Story and Screenplay.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] No documentary feature has yet been nominated for Best Picture, although *Chang* was nominated in the "Unique and Artistic Production" category at the 1927/28 awards.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] At the 3rd Academy Awards, prior to the introduction of a documentary category, *With Byrd at the South Pole* won the award for Best Cinematography, becoming the first documentary both to be nominated for and win an Oscar.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] 1952's *Navajo* would become the first film nominated for both Best Documentary and Best Cinematography.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Twelve documentaries have received nominations for Best Original Song: *Mondo Cane* (for Riz Ortolani and Nino Oliviero's "More"), *An Inconvenient Truth* (for Melissa Etheridge's "I Need to Wake Up", the only nominee from a documentary to win), *Chasing Ice* (for J.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Documentaries nominated for their scores include *This is Cinerama*, *White Wilderness* (which also won for Documentary Feature), *Let It Be*, and *Birds Do It, Bees Do It*.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Five documentary filmmakers have received honorary Oscars: Pete Smith, William L.
[src:rachel-carson/academy-award-for-best-documentary-feature] Pennebaker, Frederick Wiseman, and Agnès Varda.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Seeking inspiration from German reunification, U2 began recording *Achtung Baby* at Berlin's Hansa Studios in October 1990.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The sessions were fraught with conflict, as the band argued over their musical direction and the quality of their material.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] After tension and slow progress nearly prompted the group to disband, they made a breakthrough with the improvised writing of the song "One".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Morale and productivity improved during subsequent recording sessions in Dublin, where the album was completed in 1991.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] To confound the public's expectations of the band and their music, U2 chose the record's facetious title and colourful multi-image sleeve.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] After U2's 1987 album *The Joshua Tree* and the supporting Joshua Tree Tour brought them critical acclaim and commercial success, their 1988 double album and documentary film *Rattle and Hum* precipitated a critical backlash.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Although the record sold 14 million copies and performed well on music charts, critics were dismissive of it and the film, labelling the band's exploration of early American music as "pretentious" and "misguided and bombastic".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2's high exposure and their reputation for being overly serious led to accusations of grandiosity and self-righteousness.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2 believed that audiences misunderstood the group's collaboration with blues musician B.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] King on *Rattle and Hum* and the Lovetown Tour, and they described it as "an excursion down a dead-end street".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Bono said that, in retrospect, listening to black music enabled the group to create a work such as *Achtung Baby*, while their experiences with folk music helped him to develop as a lyricist.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] During a 30 December 1989 show near the end of the Lovetown Tour, Bono said on stage to the hometown crowd in Dublin that it was "the end of something for U2", and that "we have to go away and ... dream it all up again".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Following the tour, the group began what was at the time their longest break from public performances and album releases.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Reacting to their own sense of musical stagnation and to their critics, U2 searched for new musical ground.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] They had written "God Part II" from *Rattle and Hum* after realising they had excessively pursued nostalgia in their songwriting.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The song had a more contemporary feel that Bono said was closer to *Achtung Baby*'s direction.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Much of the material they wrote was experimental, and according to Bono, "prepar[ed] the ground for *Achtung Baby*".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Ideas deemed inappropriate for the play were put aside for the band's use.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] During this period, Bono and the Edge began increasingly writing songs together without Mullen or bassist Adam Clayton.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In mid-1990, Bono reviewed material he had written in Australia on the Lovetown Tour, and the group recorded demos at STS Studios in Dublin.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The demos later evolved into the songs "Who's Gonna Ride Your Wild Horses", "Until the End of the World", "Even Better Than the Real Thing", and "Mysterious Ways".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] After their time at STS Studios, Bono and the Edge were tasked with continuing to work on lyrics and melodies until the group reconvened.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Going into the album sessions, U2 wanted the record to completely deviate from their past work, but they were unsure how to accomplish it.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The emergence of the Madchester scene in the UK left them confused about how they would fit into any particular musical scene.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2 hired Daniel Lanois and Brian Eno to produce the album, based on the duo's prior work with the band on *The Unforgettable Fire* and *The Joshua Tree*.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Lanois was principal producer, with Mark "Flood" Ellis as engineer.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Eno took on an assisting role, working with the group in the studio for a week at a time to review their songs before leaving for a month or two.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Eno said his role was "to come in and erase anything that sounded too much like U2".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] By distancing himself from the work, he believed he provided the band with a fresh perspective on their material each time he rejoined them.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] As he explained, "I would deliberately not listen to the stuff in between visits, so I could go in cold".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Since U2 wanted the record to be harder-hitting and live-sounding, Lanois "push[ed] the performance aspect very hard, often to the point of recklessness".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The Lanois–Eno team used lateral thinking and a philosophical approach—popularised by Eno's Oblique Strategies—that contrasted with the direct and retro style of *Rattle and Hum* producer Jimmy Iovine.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The band believed that "domesticity [w]as the enemy of rock 'n' roll" and that to work on the album, they needed to remove themselves from their normal family-oriented routines.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] With a "New Europe" emerging at the end of the Cold War, they chose Berlin, in the centre of the reuniting continent, as a source of inspiration for a more European musical aesthetic.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] They chose to record at Hansa Studios in West Berlin, near the recently opened Berlin Wall.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Several acclaimed records were made at Hansa, including two from David Bowie's "Berlin Trilogy" with Eno, and Iggy Pop's *Lust for Life*.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2 arrived on 3 October 1990 on the last flight into East Berlin on the eve of German reunification.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] While looking for public celebrations, they mistakenly ended up joining an anti-unification protest by Communists.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Expecting to be inspired in Berlin, U2 instead found the city to be depressing and gloomy.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The collapse of the Berlin Wall had resulted in a state of malaise in Germany.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The band found their East Berlin hotel to be dismal and the winter inhospitable, while the location of Hansa's Studio 2 in a former SS ballroom, the Meistersaal, added to the "bad vibe".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Complicating matters, the studios had been neglected for years, forcing Eno and Lanois to import recording equipment.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Morale worsened once the sessions commenced, as the band worked long days but could not agree on a musical direction.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The Edge had been listening to electronic dance music and to industrial bands like Einstürzende Neubauten, Nine Inch Nails, the Young Gods, and KMFDM.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] He and Bono advocated new musical directions along these lines.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In contrast, Mullen was listening to classic rock acts such as Blind Faith, Cream, and Jimi Hendrix, and he was learning how to "play around the beat".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Like Clayton, he was more comfortable with a sound similar to U2's previous work and was resistant to the proposed innovations.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Further, the Edge's interest in dance club mixes and drum machines made Mullen feel that his contributions as a drummer were being diminished.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Lanois was expecting the "textural and emotional and cinematic U2" of *The Unforgettable Fire* and *The Joshua Tree*, and he did not understand the "throwaway, trashy kinds of things" on which Bono and the Edge were working.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Compounding the divisions between the two camps was a change in the band's songwriting relationship; Bono and the Edge were working more closely together, writing material without the rest of the group.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2 found that they were neither prepared nor well-rehearsed, and that their ideas were not evolving into completed songs.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The group were unable to reach consensus during their disagreements and felt that they were not making progress.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Bono and Lanois, in particular, had an argument that almost came to blows during the writing of "Mysterious Ways".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] During one tense session, Clayton removed his bass guitar and held it out to Bono, saying, "You tell me what to play and I'll play it.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Go ahead." With a sense of going nowhere, the band considered breaking up.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Eno visited for a few days, and understanding their attempts to deconstruct the band, he assured them that their progress was better than they thought.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] By adding unusual effects and sounds, he showed that the Edge's pursuit for new sonic territory was not incompatible with Mullen's and Lanois' "desire to hold on to solid song structures".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Ultimately, a breakthrough was achieved with the writing of the song "One".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] While working on "Sick Puppy"—an early version of "Mysterious Ways"—the Edge played two separate chord progressions sequentially on guitar at Lanois' encouragement, and finding inspiration, the group quickly improvised a new song that became "One".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] It provided reassurance and validated their long-standing "blank page approach" to writing and recording together.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2 returned to Dublin for Christmas, where they discussed their future together and all recommitted to the group.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Listening to the tapes, they agreed their material sounded better than they originally thought.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] They briefly returned to Berlin in January 1991 to finish their work at Hansa.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] We had to actually just put the work in and figure out the ideas and hone those ideas down." Although just two songs were delivered during their two months in Berlin, the Edge said that in retrospect, working there had been more productive and inspirational than the output had suggested.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The band had been removed from a familiar environment, providing what they described as a certain "texture and cinematic location", and many of their incomplete ideas would be revisited in the subsequent Dublin sessions with success.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In February 1991, U2 moved the album's recording sessions to the seaside manor Elsinore in the Dublin suburb of Dalkey, renting the house for £10,000 per month.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The band nicknamed the house "Dog Town" for the "tackiness" of its exterior dog kennels, and the location was credited as such in the album notes.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Lanois' strategy to record in houses, mansions, or castles was something he believed brought atmosphere to the recordings.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The group rented recording equipment from Dublin audio services company Audio Engineering, and they used a converted garage as a recording space, diagonally beneath the control room.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Video cameras and TV monitors were used to monitor and communicate between the spaces.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] With Elsinore located within walking distance of Bono's and the Edge's homes, the sessions there were more relaxed and productive.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The band struggled with one particular song—later released as the B-side "Lady With the Spinning Head"—but three separate tracks, "The Fly", "Ultraviolet (Light My Way)" and "Zoo Station", were derived from it.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] During the writing of "The Fly", Bono created a persona based on an oversized pair of black sunglasses that he wore to lighten the mood in the studio.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The character, which he also named "The Fly", evolved into a leather-clad egomaniac meant to parody rock stardom.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Bono assumed this alter ego for the band's subsequent public appearances and live performances on the Zoo TV Tour.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In April, tapes from the earlier Berlin sessions were stolen after the band reportedly left them in a hotel room, and they were subsequently leaked before the album was finished.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The recordings were bootlegged into a three-disc collection dubbed *Salome: The [Axtung Beibi] Outtakes*, named for the song "Salomé" that was prominently featured in the collection but did not make the album's final cut.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The release is considered the most famous bootleg of U2 material.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Bono dismissed the leaked demos as "gobbledygook", and the Edge likened the situation to "being violated".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The leak shook U2's confidence and soured their collective mood for a few weeks.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Staffing schedules led to the band having a surplus of engineers at one point, and as a result, they split recording between Elsinore and the Edge's home studio to increase productivity.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Engineer Robbie Adams said the approach raised morale and activity levels: "There was always something different to listen to, always something exciting happening." The band's desire to record everything they played in the studio posed a challenge to the production team.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The focus on capturing the band's material and encouraging the best performances meant that little attention was paid to combating audio spill, aside from placing the Edge's and Clayton's amplifiers in separate rooms.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In issue 14 of U2's fan magazine *Propaganda*, Lanois said that he believed some of the in-progress songs would become worldwide hits, despite lyrics and vocal takes being unfinished.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] During the Dublin sessions, Eno was sent tapes of the previous two months' work, which he called a "total disaster".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Joining U2 in the studio, he stripped away what he thought to be excessive overdubbing.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The group believes his intervention saved the album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Eno theorised that the band was too close to their music, explaining: "if you know a piece of music terribly well and the mix changes and the bass guitar goes very quiet, you still hear the bass.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] You're so accustomed to it being there that you compensate and remake it in your mind." Eno also assisted them through a crisis point one month before the recording deadline; he recalled that "everything seemed like a mess", and he insisted the band take a two-week holiday.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The break gave them a clearer perspective and added decisiveness.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] After work at Elsinore finished in July, the sessions moved to Windmill Lane Studios where Eno, Flood, Lanois, and previous U2 producer Steve Lillywhite mixed the tracks.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Each producer created his own mixes of the songs, and the band either picked the version they preferred or requested that certain aspects of each be combined.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Additional recording and mixing continued at a frenetic pace until the 21 September deadline, including last-minute changes to "The Fly", "One", and "Mysterious Ways".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The Edge estimated that half of the sessions' work was done in the last three weeks to finalise songs.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The final night was spent devising a running order for the record.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The following day, the Edge travelled to Los Angeles with the album's tapes for mastering.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2 is credited with composing the music for all of *Achtung Baby*'s tracks, despite periods of separated songwriting.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] They wrote the music primarily through jam sessions, a common practice for them.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The album represents a deviation from the sound of their past work; the songs are less anthemic in nature, and their musical style demonstrates a more European aesthetic, introducing influences from alternative rock, industrial music, and electronic dance music.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The band referred to the album's musical departure as "the sound of four men chopping down The Joshua Tree".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Accordingly, the distorted introduction to the opening track "Zoo Station" was intended to make listeners think the record was broken or was mistakenly not the new U2 album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Author Susan Fast said that with the group's use of technology in the song's opening, "there can be no mistake that U2 has embraced sound resources new to them".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] For the album, the Edge often eschewed his normally minimalistic approach to guitar playing and his trademark chiming, delay-heavy sound, in favour of a style that incorporated more solos, dissonance, and feedback.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Industrial influences and guitar effects, particularly distortion, contributed to a "metallic" style and "harder textures".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Music journalist Bill Wyman said the Edge's guitar playing on the closing track "Love Is Blindness" sounded like a "dentist's drill".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The Edge achieved breakthroughs in the writing of songs such as "Even Better Than the Real Thing" and "Mysterious Ways" by toying with various effects units.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The rhythm section is more pronounced in the mix on *Achtung Baby*, and hip hop-inspired electronic dance beats are featured on many of the album's tracks, most prominently "The Fly".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Elysa Gardner of *Rolling Stone* compared the layering of dance beats into guitar-heavy mixes to songs by British bands Happy Mondays and Jesus Jones.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] "Mysterious Ways" combines a funky guitar riff with a danceable, conga-laden beat, for what Bono called "U2 at our funkiest ...
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Sly and The Family Stone meets Madchester baggy." Amidst layers of distorted guitars, "The Fly" and "Zoo Station" feature industrial-influenced percussion—the timbre of Mullen's drums exhibits a "cold, processed sound, something like beating on a tin can", according to author Albin Zak.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Whereas Bono exhibited a full-throated vocal delivery on the group's previous releases, for *Achtung Baby* he extended his range into a lower register and used what Fast described as "breathy and subdued colors".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] On many tracks, including "The Fly" and "Zoo Station", he sang as a character; one technique used is octave doubling, in which the vocals are doubled but sung in two different octaves.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] This octave differentiation was sometimes done with vocals simultaneously, while at other times, it distinguishes voices between the verses and choruses.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] According to Fast, the technique introduces "a contrasting lyrical idea and vocal character to deliver it", leading to both literal and ironic interpretations of Bono's vocals.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] He said that lowering his voice helped him find a new vocal vocabulary, as he previously felt limited to "certain words and tones" by his tenor voice.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Other methods of altering his vocals included treating them with processing and feeding them through a distortion pedal.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] These techniques were all used to give his voice a different emotional feel and distinguish it from his previous work.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] As is often the case on U2 albums, Bono is credited as the sole lyricist.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In contrast to U2's previous records, whose lyrics were politically and socially charged, *Achtung Baby* is more personal and introspective, examining love, sexuality, spirituality, faith, and betrayal.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The lyrics are darker in tone, describing troubled personal relationships and exuding feelings of confusion, loneliness, and inadequacy.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Lyrics were inspired by the dissolution of the Edge's marriage, as well as that of another of Bono's friends.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] During the album's recording, the Edge separated from his wife (the mother of three of his children), and the pain he felt resulted in him dedicating himself to the record and advocating for more personal themes.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Bono found inspiration from his own personal life, citing the births of his two daughters in 1989 and 1991 as major influences.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] This is reflected in "Zoo Station", which opens the album as a statement of intent with lyrics suggesting new anticipations and appetites.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Of the album's personal nature, Bono said that there were a lot of "blood and guts" in it.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] His lyrics to the ballad "One" were inspired by the band members' interpersonal struggles and the German reunification.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The Edge described the song on one level as a "bitter, twisted, vitriolic conversation between two people who've been through some nasty, heavy stuff".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Similarly, "Ultraviolet (Light My Way)" describes a strained relationship and unease over obligations, and on "Acrobat", Bono sings about weakness, hypocrisy, and inadequacy.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2 biographer Bill Flanagan credits Bono's habit of keeping his lyrics "in flux until the last minute" with providing a narrative coherence to the album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Flanagan interpreted *Achtung Baby* as using the moon as a metaphor for a dark woman seducing the singer away from his virtuous love, the sun; he is tempted away from domestic life by an exciting nightlife and tests how far he can go before returning home.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Despite the record's darker themes, many lyrics are more flippant and sexual than those from the band's previous work.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] This reflects the group's revisiting some of the Dadaist characters and stage antics they dabbled with in the late 1970s as teenagers but abandoned for more literal themes in the 1980s.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] While the band had previously been opposed to materialism, they examined and flirted with this value on the album and the Zoo TV Tour.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The title and lyrics of "Even Better Than the Real Thing" are "reflective of the times [the band] were living in, when people were no longer looking for the truth, [they] were all looking for instant gratification".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] "Trashy" and "throwaway" were among the band's buzzwords during recording, leading to many tracks in this vein.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The chorus of "Ultraviolet (Light My Way)" features the pop lyrical cliché "baby, baby, baby", juxtaposed against the dark lyrics in the verses.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Bono wrote the lyrics to "The Fly" in character as the song's eponymous persona by composing a sequence of aphorisms.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] He called the song "like a crank call from Hell ... but [the caller] likes it there".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Religious imagery is present throughout the record.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] "Until the End of the World" is an imagined conversation between Jesus Christ and his betrayer, Judas Iscariot.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] On "Acrobat", Bono sings about feelings of spiritual alienation in the line "I'd break bread and wine / If there was a church I could receive in".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In many tracks, Bono's lyrics about women carry religious connotations, describing them as spirits, life, light, and idols to be worshipped.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Religious interpretations of the album are the subject of the book *Meditations on Love in the Shadow of the Fall* from the *33 ⅓* series.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The sleeve artwork for *Achtung Baby* was designed by two employees from the design firm Works Associates: Steve Averill, U2's long-time album cover designer; and Shaughn McGrath, who had just joined the firm.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] To parallel the band's change in musical direction, Averill and McGrath devised sleeve concepts that used multiple colour images to contrast with the seriousness of the individual, mostly monochromatic images from previous U2 album sleeves.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Rough sketches and designs were created early during the recording sessions, and some experimental designs were conceived to closely resemble dance music sleeves.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Averill said: "We just did them to show how extreme we could go and then everyone came back to levels that they were happy with.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] An initial photo shoot with the band's long-time photographer Anton Corbijn was conducted near U2's Berlin hotel in late 1990.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Most of the photos were black-and-white, and the group felt they were not indicative of the spirit of the new album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] They recommissioned Corbijn for an additional two-week photo shoot in Tenerife in February 1991, for which they dressed up and mingled with the crowds of the annual Carnival of Santa Cruz de Tenerife, presenting a more playful side of themselves.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] It was during the group's time in Tenerife and during a four-day shoot in Morocco in July that they were photographed in drag.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Additional photos were taken in a Dublin studio in June, a session in which Corbijn captured long exposures over several minutes.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] One of the photos from this session depicted a naked Clayton.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Overall, Corbijn's images for *Achtung Baby* were intended to confound expectations of U2, and their full colour contrasted with the monochromatic imagery on past sleeves.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] For the photoshoots in Berlin and Tenerife, the band were photographed with brightly painted Trabants, East German automobiles that became a symbol of the fall of Communism and for which the band had developed an affection.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Street artist Thierry Noir was commissioned to provide the artwork and painted the vehicles in Hansa Studios' parking lot; he became involved through a fellow collaborator of the band's, film director Wim Wenders.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Images of the band with the Trabants appear on the sleeve and throughout the album booklet.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] These vehicles were later incorporated into the Zoo TV Tour set design as part of the lighting system.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Several photographs were considered as candidates for a single cover image, including shots of: a cow on an Irish farm in County Kildare; the nude Clayton; and the band driving a Trabant.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Ultimately, a multiple image scheme was used, as U2, Corbijn, Averill, and the producers thought that "the sense of flux expressed by both the music and the band's playing with alter egos was best articulated by the lack of a single viewpoint".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The resulting front sleeve is arranged as a 4×4 square grid.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] A mix of Corbijn's original images from Berlin and the later photo shoots was used, as the band wanted to balance the "colder European feel of the mainly black-and-white Berlin images with the much warmer exotic climates of Santa Cruz and Morocco".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Some photographs were used because they were striking on their own, while others were used because of their ambiguity.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The nude photo of Clayton was placed on the rear cover of the record.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] After objections to the photo were raised in the United States, it was censored; Averill and McGrath painted a black "X" and faxed it to the record label, which turned it into a sticker that American distributors and retailers could affix to the album packaging to cover Clayton's genitals.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Compact disc and cassette copies were censored with the sticker, while vinyl editions featured the photo uncensored.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] To "match the gush of spontaneity and power of the photography", McGrath calligraphed the album title, band name, and track listing for the packaging, using paintbrushes as well as ink and pen.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Contrasting with the "unique humanity" of his handwriting, McGrath set the lyrics and album credits in the ubiquitous European font Helvetica, "mirror[ing] the repetitive industrial and Germanic themes of the album".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The label of the physical CD and vinyl disc features an image of a "babyface" graffitied by artist Charlie Whisker onto an external wall of Windmill Lane Studios and photographed by Richie Smyth.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The babyface image was later adopted as a logo for Zoo TV Tour memorabilia and was incorporated into the *Zooropa* album cover.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In 2003, music television network VH1 ranked *Achtung Baby*'s sleeve at number 39 on its list of the "50 Greatest Album Covers".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Bono has called the sleeve his favourite U2 cover artwork.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The German word **Achtung** (German: [ˈaxtʊŋ] ⓘ) in the album title is an interjection that translates into English as "attention" or "watch out".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] There are multiple reports of the origins of the album's title.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] According to singer Tottie Goldsmith, she often used the phrase "Achtung, baby" to get her boyfriend's attention and was once overheard by Bono at a party in 1989, who "turned around to ask her why she had just said that".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Goldsmith has said that inspiring the album title became her "claim to fame".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] According to Bono, U2's sound engineer Joe O'Herlihy said the phrase "Achtung, baby" often during the recording sessions, using it as a "call to arms" each time the band were about to begin work for the day.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] He reportedly took it from Mel Brooks's 1967 film *The Producers*; however, the phrase is not spoken in the film and actually originated from Brooks's 1983 comedy hip hop song "To Be or Not to Be (The Hitler Rap)".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The album title was selected in August 1991 near the end of the album sessions.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Bono thought it was an ideal title, as it was attention-grabbing to him, referenced Germany, and hinted at either romance or birth, both of which were themes on the album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The band were determined not to highlight the seriousness of the lyrics and instead sought to "erect a mask" with the title, a concept that was further developed on the Zoo TV Tour, particularly through Bono's characters such as "The Fly".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Of the title, he said in 1992: "It's a con, in a way.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] We call it *Achtung Baby*, grinning up our sleeves in all the photography.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] But it's probably the heaviest record we've ever made ...
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] U2 considered several other titles for the album, including *Man* (in contrast to the group's debut, *Boy*), *69*, *Zoo Station*, and *Adam*, the latter of which would have been paired with the nude photo of Clayton.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Other titles in consideration included *Fear of Women* and *Cruise Down Main Street*, the latter a reference to the Rolling Stones' record *Exile on Main St.* and the cruise missiles launched on Baghdad during the Gulf War.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Most of the proposed titles were rejected out of the belief that people would see them as pretentious and "another Big Statement from U2".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] As early as December 1990, the music press reported that U2 would be recording a dance-oriented album and that it would be released in mid-1991.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In August 1991, sound collage artists Negativland released an EP entitled *U2* that parodied U2's song "I Still Haven't Found What I'm Looking For".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Island Records objected to the release, believing consumers would confuse the EP for a new U2 record.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Island successfully sued for copyright infringement but were criticised in the music press, as were U2, although the band were not involved in the litigation.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Island Records and U2 refused to make advance copies of the album available to the press until just a few days before the release date, preferring that fans listen to the record before reading reviews.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The decision came amid rumours of tensions within the band, and journalist David Browne compared it to the Hollywood practice of withholding pre-release copies of films from reviewers whenever they receive poor word-of-mouth press.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] *Achtung Baby* was released on 18 November 1991 in the UK and 19 November in the US on compact disc, cassette tape, and vinyl record, with an initial shipment of more than 1.4 million copies in the US.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The album was the first release by a major act to use two so-called "eco-friendly" packages—the cardboard Digipak, and the shrinkwrapped jewel case without the longbox cardboard attachment.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Island encouraged record stores to order the jewel case packaging by offering a four-percent discount.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] "Mysterious Ways" was released as the second single five days after the release of *Achtung Baby*.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] On the US *Billboard* charts, the song topped the Modern Rock Tracks and Album Rock Tracks charts, and it reached number nine on the Hot 100.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Elsewhere, it reached number one in Canada and number three in Australia.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Three additional commercial singles were released in 1992.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] "One", released in March at the beginning of the Zoo TV Tour, reached number seven in the UK and number ten in the US charts.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Like its predecessor, it topped the Modern Rock Tracks chart, and the singles charts in Canada and Ireland.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The song has since become regarded as one of the greatest of all time, ranking highly on many critics' lists.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The fourth single from *Achtung Baby*, "Even Better Than the Real Thing", was released in June.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The album version of the song peaked at number 12 on the UK Singles Chart, while reaching number one on the US Album Rock Tracks chart.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] A "Perfecto" remix of the song by DJ Paul Oakenfold performed better in the UK than the album version did, peaking at number eight.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] "Who's Gonna Ride Your Wild Horses" followed as the fifth and final single in November 1992.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] It peaked at number 14 on the UK Singles Chart, and number two on the US Album Rock Tracks chart.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] All five commercial singles charted within the top 20 in Ireland, Australia, Canada, and the UK.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Promotional singles for "Until the End of the World", "Salomé", and "Zoo Station" were also released.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In October 1992, U2 released *Achtung Baby: The Videos, the Cameos, and a Whole Lot of Interference from Zoo TV*, a VHS and LaserDisc compilation of nine music videos from the album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Running for 65 minutes, it was produced by Ned O'Hanlon and released by Island and PolyGram.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] It included three music videos each for "One" and "Even Better than the Real Thing", along with videos for "The Fly", "Mysterious Ways", and "Until the End of the World".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Interspersed between the music videos were clips of so-called "interference", comprising documentary footage, media clips, and other video similar to what was displayed at Zoo TV Tour concerts.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The release was certified platinum in the US, and gold in Canada.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The success of *Achtung Baby* and the Zoo TV Tour re-established U2 as one of the most popular and critically acclaimed musical acts in the world.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The group nearly swept *Rolling Stone*'s 1992 end-of-year readers' polls, winning honours for "Best Single" ("One"), "Artist of the Year", "Best Album", "Best Songwriter" (Bono), "Best Album Cover", and "Comeback of the Year", among others.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Critics at several newspapers, such as *The Washington Post*, *The Boston Globe*, and the *Chicago Sun-Times*, ranked the album among the year's best.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The album placed fourth on the "Best Albums" list from *The Village Voice*'s 1991 Pazz & Jop critics' poll.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] It was shortlisted for the 1992 Mercury Music Prize.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] At the 35th Annual Grammy Awards, *Achtung Baby* won the award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal and was nominated for Album of the Year, and it earned Lanois and Eno the award for Producer of the Year (Non-Classical).
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] At the American Music Awards of 1993, *Achtung Baby* was nominated for Favorite Pop/Rock Album, and at the Juno Awards of 1993, it was nominated for Best Selling Album (Foreign or Domestic).
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] In 2024, *Achtung Baby* was selected as the winner of the RTÉ Choice Music Prize for Classic Irish Album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] According to Nielsen Soundscan, *Achtung Baby* had sold 4.9 million copies in the US by February 1997 and 5.5 million copies by March 2009.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] It has been certified 8× platinum in the US by the RIAA.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] The record has been certified 5× platinum in Australia, 4× platinum in the UK, and diamond in Canada, the highest certification award.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] Overall, 18 million copies have been sold worldwide.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p01] It is U2's second-highest-selling record after *The Joshua Tree*, which has sold 25 million copies.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Following the release of *Achtung Baby*, U2 staged a worldwide concert tour, titled the Zoo TV Tour.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Like *Achtung Baby*, the tour was intended to deviate from the band's past.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] In contrast to the austere stage setups of previous U2 tours, Zoo TV was an elaborately staged multimedia event.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] It satirised television and the viewing public's overstimulation by attempting to instill "sensory overload" in its audience.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The stage featured large video screens that showed visual effects, random video clips from pop culture, and flashing text phrases.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The shows incorporated channel surfing, prank calls, video confessionals, a belly dancer, and live satellite transmissions with war-torn Sarajevo.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Whereas the group were known for their earnest live act in the 1980s, their Zoo TV performances were intentionally ironic and self-deprecating; on stage, Bono portrayed several characters he conceived, including "The Fly", "Mirror Ball Man", and "MacPhisto".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The majority of the album's songs were played at each show, and the set lists began with up to eight consecutive *Achtung Baby* songs as a further sign that they were no longer the U2 of the 1980s.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The tour began in February 1992 and comprised 157 shows over almost two years.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] During a six-month break, the band recorded the album *Zooropa*, which was released in July 1993.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] It was inspired by Zoo TV and expanded on its themes of technology and media oversaturation.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] By the time the tour concluded in December 1993, it had sold about 5.3 million tickets and reportedly grossed US$151 million.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] In 2002, *Q* magazine said the Zoo TV Tour was "still the most spectacular rock tour staged by any band".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The tour's 27 November 1993 concert in Sydney was filmed and commercially released as *Zoo TV: Live from Sydney* by PolyGram in May 1994.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] For the band, *Achtung Baby* was a watershed that secured their creative future, and its success led to the group's continued musical experimentation during the 1990s.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] *Zooropa*, released in 1993, was a further departure for the band, incorporating additional dance music influences and electronic effects into their sound.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] In 1995, U2 and Brian Eno collaborated on the experimental/ambient album *Original Soundtracks 1* under the pseudonym "Passengers".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] For *Pop* in 1997, the group's experiences with dance club culture and their usage of tape loops, programming, rhythm sequencing, and sampling resulted in their most dance-oriented album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The 20th anniversary of *Achtung Baby* was marked by several releases in 2011.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] At the band's request, a documentary film about the album entitled *From the Sky Down* was produced.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] It was directed by Davis Guggenheim, who previously collaborated with the Edge for the documentary *It Might Get Loud* in 2008.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] *From the Sky Down* documents the album's difficult recording period, the band members' relationships, and U2's creative process.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Archival footage and stills from the recording sessions appear in the film, along with unreleased scenes from *Rattle and Hum*.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] For the documentary, the band were filmed during a return visit to Hansa Studios and during rehearsals for the Glastonbury Festival 2011.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The film premiered at the 2011 Toronto International Film Festival, becoming the first documentary to open the festival, and in October, it was broadcast on multiple television networks worldwide.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] On 31 October 2011, *Achtung Baby* was reissued in five formats.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] In addition to a single-disc release of the album, a deluxe edition included a bonus disc of remixes and B-sides from the album's five singles, and a vinyl edition included the album on two LPs with two additional LPs of remixes.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The "Über Deluxe" edition also contains a double-vinyl copy of the album, five 7-inch vinyl singles, a copy of U2's fan club magazine *Propaganda*, and a replica of Bono's "Fly" sunglasses.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The media initially reported that the reissue was a remastered release.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] However, the reissue's official website initially excluded any mention of "remastering" before adding it and then removing it.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The Edge confirmed that the album was not fully remastered since "the original was so right" and so much "artistry had gone into the original EQ'ing" but did say that they were able to "optimize it ... tweak the levels, give it a bit of a polish".
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] "Blow Your House Down", an outtake included in the deluxe editions, was released as a promotional single in October 2011.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Continuing a campaign by U2 to reissue all of their records on vinyl, *Achtung Baby* was re-released on two 180-gram vinyl records on 27 July 2018.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Unlike the 2011 reissue, the album was remastered for its 2018 reissue, with direction from the Edge.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Each copy includes a download card that can be used to redeem a digital copy of the album.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] In 2021, *Achtung Baby* was re-released in several formats for its 30th anniversary: standard black vinyl and deluxe colour vinyl editions were released on 19 November, followed by a 50-track digital box set on 3 December.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The band also collaborated with Thierry Noir on an art installation held at Hansa Studios; Noir, who painted the original Trabants featured in the album photography, contributed new artwork to a Trabant and a section of the Berlin Wall for the exhibition.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The bonnet of the car was auctioned to benefit the Berlin Institute for Sound and Music.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] In January 2024, a Dolby Atmos surround sound mix of *Achtung Baby* was digitally released to streaming platforms.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] It was the first album from U2's catalogue to be released in the format.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Mixing was done in five studios globally over a 17-month period.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] From September 2023 to March 2024, U2 staged a 40-date concert residency called U2:UV *Achtung Baby* Live to inaugurate the concert venue Sphere in the Las Vegas Valley.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The shows featured a full performance of *Achtung Baby* and leveraged the venue's immersive video and sound capabilities.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Mullen did not participate in the concerts in order to recuperate from surgery, marking the first time since 1978 that U2 performed without him; Dutch drummer Bram van den Berg from the band Krezip filled in.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] The residency grossed $244.5 million from 663,000 tickets sold, making it the fourth-highest-grossing concert residency of all time.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] All lyrics are written by Bono; all music is composed by U2.
[src:rachel-carson/achtung-baby-p02] Personnel taken from *Achtung Baby* CD booklet.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] Stamp was born in Catonsville, Maryland.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] Stamp grew up in Catonsville, approximately 20 miles from the University of Maryland, College Park campus where she would work for nearly four decades.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] Timothy's School and Western High School.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] Between 1913 and 1915, Stamp taught physical education at Catonsville High School.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] During the summers of 1914 and 1915, she enrolled in a "College Courses for Teachers" program at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] Stamp then enrolled at Sophie Newcomb College (the women's school associated with Tulane University).
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] She spent the summers of 1915 and 1916 teaching physical education at Alfred University (in western New York State), and she returned to Maryland in the summer of 1917 to serve as summer school instructor at the University of Maryland.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] As World War I approached, Stamp applied her experience as a recreation director and classwork in sociology as a social worker for the War Work Council of the Young Women's Christian Association (YWCA), where she formed recreation programs for female factory workers.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] She led recreation education for the 5,000 women employed at the Old Hickory Munitions Plant (external link) in Jacksonville, Tennessee 1918–1919.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] During 1919 and 1920 Stamp served as the director of recreation for female workers at the Industrial Service Center of the YWCA in New Orleans while finishing her studies at Newcomb College.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] In 1921, Stamp graduated from with a degree in sociology.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] After graduation, Stamp accepted a position with the Red Cross as a field representative in the South.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] Soon after, University of Maryland president Albert F.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] Woods offered her the position of Dean of Women, which she accepted.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] Stamp served as Dean of Women at the University of Maryland, College Park for 38 years.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] She initially took the position as a one-year contract, which was renewed for a second year before being extended to comprise the remainder of her career.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] The university had just begun admitting women in 1916.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] During Stamp's tenure as Dean of Women, enrollment of female students increased from 93 in 1922 to approximately 4,000 in 1960.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] In 1923, she organized the Maryland State Association of Deans of Women, which soon gained membership from neighboring Delaware, Virginia, and Washington, DC.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] In 1924, Stamp earned a master's degree in sociology at the University of Maryland, where she completed a thesis entitled "Community Organization in Maryland Welfare Organization." She undertook additional graduate work at Catholic University of America and American University.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] When Stamp retired in December 1960, the University of Maryland Board of Regents awarded Stamp the title *dean of women emeritus*.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] *Emeritus* is the highest faculty honor bestowed by the board, and Stamp the first to receive the title.
[src:rachel-carson/adele-hagner-stamp] The Baltimore Sun, reporting on her retirement, mused that her 38 years of service was likely the "longest record of continuous service at a single school of any dean of women in the United States" (page 11).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson began her career as an aquatic biologist in the U.S.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Bureau of Fisheries, and became a full-time nature writer in the 1950s.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her widely praised 1951 bestseller *The Sea Around Us* won her a U.S.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] National Book Award, recognition as a gifted writer, and financial security.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Its success prompted the republication of her first book, *Under the Sea Wind* (1941), in 1952, which was followed by *The Edge of the Sea*in 1955 — both were also bestsellers.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] This sea trilogy explores the whole of ocean life from the shores to the depths.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Late in the 1950s, Carson turned her attention to conservation, especially some problems she believed were caused by synthetic pesticides.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The result was the book *Silent Spring* (1962), which brought environmental concerns to an unprecedented share of the American people.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Although *Silent Spring* was met with fierce opposition by chemical companies, it spurred a reversal in national pesticide policy, which led to a nationwide ban on DDT and other pesticides.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] It also inspired a grassroots environmental movement that led to the creation of the U.S.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson was posthumously awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Jimmy Carter.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson was born on May 27, 1907, on a family farm near Springdale, Pennsylvania, located by the Allegheny River near Pittsburgh.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She was the daughter of Maria Frazier (McLean) and Robert Warden Carson, an insurance salesman.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She spent a lot of time exploring around her family's 65-acre (26 ha) farm.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] An avid reader, she began writing stories, often involving animals, at age eight.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] At age ten, she had her first story published.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Nicholas Magazine*, which carried her first published stories, the works of Beatrix Potter, the novels of Gene Stratton-Porter, and in her teen years, Herman Melville, Joseph Conrad, and Robert Louis Stevenson.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The natural world, particularly that of the ocean, was the common thread of her favorite literature.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson attended Springdale's small school through tenth grade, and then completed high school in nearby Parnassus, Pennsylvania, graduating in 1925 at the top of her class of 44 students.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In high school, Carson was said to have been somewhat of a loner.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson gained admission to Pennsylvania College for Women, now Chatham University, in Pittsburgh, where she originally studied English but switched her major to biology in January 1928.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She continued contributing to the school's student newspaper and literary supplement.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She was admitted to graduate school at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore in 1928, but was forced to remain at the Pennsylvania College for Women for her senior year due to financial difficulties.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 1929, she graduated *magna cum laude*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In the summer of 1929, Carson moved to Woods Hole, Massachusetts for a course at the Marine Biological Laboratory (MBL).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] While at MBL, Carson wrote a "detailed anatomical study of the brain and cranial nerves of a turtle".
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her time at MBL had a profound impact on Carson, who later stated that her "first prolonged contact with the sea [was] at Woods Hole", where she "first discovered the scientific literature of the sea".
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] That fall, she continued her studies in zoology and genetics at Johns Hopkins.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] After her first year of graduate school, Carson became a part-time student, taking an assistantship in Raymond Pearl's laboratory, where she worked with rats and *Drosophila*, to earn money for tuition.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] After false starts with pit vipers and squirrels, she completed a dissertation on the embryonic development of the pronephros (urinary organ) in fish.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In June 1932, she earned a master's degree in zoology.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She had intended to continue for a doctorate, however in 1934 Carson was forced to leave Johns Hopkins to search for a full-time teaching position to help support her family during the Great Depression.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 1935, Carson's father died suddenly, worsening their already critical financial situation and leaving Carson to care for her aging mother.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] At the urging of Mary Scott Skinker, her undergraduate biology mentor, Carson secured a temporary position with the U.S.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Bureau of Fisheries, where she wrote radio copy for a series of weekly educational broadcasts called *Romance Under the Waters*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The series of 52 seven-minute programs focused on aquatic life and was intended to generate public interest in fish biology and the bureau's work, a task that several writers before Carson had not managed.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson also began submitting articles on marine life in the Chesapeake Bay, based on her research for the series, to local newspapers and magazines.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson earned extra money as a lecturer at the University of Maryland's Dental and Pharmacy Schools and Johns Hopkins University.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson's supervisor, pleased with the success of the radio series, asked her to write the introduction to a public brochure about the fisheries bureau; he also worked to secure her the first full-time position that became available.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Sitting for the civil service exam, she outscored all other applicants and, in 1936, became the second woman hired by the Bureau of Fisheries for a full-time professional position, as a junior aquatic biologist.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Using her research and consultations with marine biologists as starting points, she wrote a steady stream of articles for *The Baltimore Sun* and other newspapers.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, her family responsibilities further increased in January 1937 when her older sister died, leaving Carson as the sole breadwinner for her mother and two nieces.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In July 1937, the *Atlantic Monthly* accepted a revised version of an essay, *The World of Waters*, that she originally wrote for her first fisheries bureau brochure.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her supervisor had deemed it too good for that purpose.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The essay, published as *Undersea*, was a vivid narrative of a journey along the ocean floor.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] It marked a major turning point in Carson's writing career.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Publishing house Simon & Schuster, impressed by *Undersea*, contacted Carson and suggested that she expand it into a book.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Several years of writing resulted in *Under the Sea Wind* (1941), which received excellent reviews but sold poorly.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In the meantime, Carson's article-writing success continued with her features appearing in *Sun Magazine*, *Nature*, and *Collier's*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson attempted to leave the Bureau (by then transformed into the United States Fish and Wildlife Service) in 1945.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, few jobs for naturalists were available, since most money for science was focused on technical fields in the wake of the Manhattan Project.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In mid-1945, Carson first encountered the subject of DDT, a revolutionary new pesticide—lauded as the "insect bomb" after the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki—that was only beginning to undergo tests for safety and ecological effects.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] DDT was one of Carson's many writing interests at the time, but editors found the subject unappealing; she published nothing on DDT until 1962.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson rose within the Fish and Wildlife Service, and in 1945 was supervising a small writing staff.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 1949, she was appointed chief editor of publications, which allowed her increased opportunities for fieldwork and freedom in choosing her writing projects; however, it also entailed increasingly tedious administrative responsibilities.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] By 1948, Carson was working on material for a second book and decided to begin a transition to writing full-time.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] That year, she took on a literary agent, Marie Rodell; they formed a close professional relationship that would last the rest of Carson's career.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Oxford University Press expressed interest in Carson's book proposal for a life history of the ocean, spurring her to complete by early 1950 the manuscript of what would become *The Sea Around Us*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Chapters appeared in *Science Digest* and *The Yale Review*, which published a chapter, "The Birth of an Island," which won the American Association for the Advancement of Science's George Westinghouse Science Writing Prize.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Beginning in June 1951, nine chapters were serialized in *The New Yorker*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] On July 2, 1951, the book was published by Oxford University Press.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] *The Sea Around Us* remained on *The New York Times* Bestseller List for 86 weeks, was abridged by *Reader's Digest*, won the 1952 National Book Award for Nonfiction and the John Burroughs Medal, and resulted in Carson being awarded two honorary doctorates.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She licensed a documentary film based on it, *The Sea*, whose success led to republication of *Under the Sea Wind*, which became a bestseller.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] With success came financial security; in 1952, Carson was able to give up her job in order to concentrate on writing full-time.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson was inundated with requests for speaking engagements, fan mail and other correspondence regarding *The Sea Around Us*, along with work on the script that she had secured the right to review.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] This led to many scientific inconsistencies inside the film.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Despite Carson's requests to resolve these problems, Allen went forward with the script.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] He succeeded in producing a very successful documentary.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] It went on to win the 1953 Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, Carson was so embittered by the experience that she never again sold film rights to her work.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Freeman in the summer of 1953 on Southport Island, Maine.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Freeman had written to Carson welcoming her to the area when she had heard that the famous author was to become her neighbor.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] It was the beginning of a devoted friendship that lasted the rest of Carson's life.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Their relationship was conducted mainly through letters and during summers spent together in Maine.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Over 12 years, they exchanged around 900 letters.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Many of these were published in the book *Always, Rachel*, published in 1995 by Beacon Press.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Lear, writes that "Carson sorely needed a devoted friend and kindred spirit who would listen to her without advising and accept her wholly, the writer as well as the woman." She found this in Freeman.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The two women had common interests, nature chief among them, and began exchanging letters regularly while apart.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] They shared summers for the remainder of Carson's life and met whenever else their schedules permitted.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Concerning the depth of their relationship, commentators have said: "the expression of their love was limited almost wholly to letters and very occasional farewell kisses or holding of hands".
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Freeman shared parts of Carson's letters with her husband to help him understand the relationship, but much of their correspondence was carefully guarded.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Some believe Freeman and Carson's relationship was romantic in nature.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] One of the letters from Carson to Freeman reads: "But, oh darling, I want to be with you so terribly that it hurts!", while in another, Freeman writes: "I love you beyond expression...
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Shortly before Carson's death, she and Freeman destroyed hundreds of letters.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] According to her biographer, Linda Lear, there was a disagreement about the final arrangements for Rachel.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her brother, Robert Carson, insisted that her cremated remains be buried beside their mother in Maryland.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] This was against her wishes to be buried in Maine.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson's wishes were carried out by an organizing committee, including her agent (Marie Rodell), her editor (Paul Brooks), and Dorothy Freeman.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In the spring of 1964, Dorothy received half of Rachel's ashes in the mail sent to her by Robert Carson.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In the summer of that year, Dorothy carried out Rachel's final wishes, scattering her ashes along the rocky shores of Sheepscot Bay in Maine.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Early in 1953, Carson began library and field research on the ecology and organisms of the Atlantic shore.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 1955, she completed the third volume of her sea trilogy, *The Edge of the Sea*, which focuses on life in coastal ecosystems, particularly along the Eastern Seaboard.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] It appeared in *The New Yorker* in two condensed installments shortly before its October 26 book release by Houghton Mifflin (again a new publisher).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] By this time, Carson's reputation for clear and poetical prose was well established; *The Edge of the Sea* received highly favorable reviews, if not quite as enthusiastic as for *The Sea Around Us*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Through 1955 and 1956, Carson worked on several projects—including the script for an *Omnibus* episode, "Something About the Sky"—and wrote articles for popular magazines.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her plan for the next book was to address evolution.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, the publication of Julian Huxley's *Evolution in Action*—and her own difficulty in finding a clear and compelling approach to the topic—led her to abandon the project.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Instead, her interests were turning to conservation.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She considered an environment-themed book project tentatively titled *Remembrance of the Earth* and became involved with The Nature Conservancy and other conservation groups.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In early 1957, a family tragedy struck for the third time when one of her nieces she had cared for since the 1940s died at the age of 31, leaving her 5-year-old son, Roger Christie, an orphan.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson took on the responsibility for Roger when she adopted him, along with caring for her aging mother.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson moved to Silver Spring, Maryland to care for Roger and spent much of 1957 putting together a new living situation and studying specific environmental threats.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] By late 1957, Carson was closely following federal proposals for widespread pesticide spraying; the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) planned to eradicate fire ants.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Other spraying programs involving chlorinated hydrocarbons and organophosphates were on the rise.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] For the rest of her life, Carson's main professional focus would be the dangers of pesticide overuse.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Starting in the mid-1940s, Carson had become concerned about the use of synthetic pesticides, many of which had been developed through the military funding of science since World War II.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, the United States federal government's 1957 gypsy moth, now called spongy moth, eradication program prompted Carson to devote her research and her next book to pesticides and environmental poisons.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The gypsy moth program involved aerial spraying of DDT and other pesticides mixed with fuel oil, including the spraying of private land.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Landowners on Long Island filed a lawsuit to have the spraying stopped, and many in affected regions followed the case closely.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Though the suit was lost, the Supreme Court granted petitioners the right to gain injunctions against potential environmental damage in the future; this laid the basis for later successful environmental actions.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The Audubon Naturalist Society also actively opposed such spraying programs and recruited Carson to help make public the government's exact spraying practices and the related research.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson began the four-year project of what would become *Silent Spring* by gathering examples of environmental damage attributed to DDT.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She also attempted to enlist others to join the cause, such as essayist E.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] White and several journalists and scientists.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] By 1958, Carson had arranged a book deal, with plans to co-write with *Newsweek* science journalist Edwin Diamond.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, when *The New Yorker* commissioned a long and well-paid article on the topic from Carson, she began considering writing more than simply the introduction and conclusion as planned; soon, it was a solo project.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] (Diamond would later write one of the harshest critiques of *Silent Spring*).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] As her research progressed, Carson found a sizable community of scientists who were documenting the physiological and environmental effects of pesticides.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She also took advantage of her connections with many government scientists, who supplied her with confidential information.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She also found significant support and extensive evidence from a group of biodynamic agriculture organic market gardeners, their adviser, Dr.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Ehrenfried Pfeiffer, other contacts, and their suite of legal actions (1957–1960) against the U.S.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] According to recent research by Paull (2013), this may have been the primary and (for strategic reasons) uncredited source for Carson's book.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Richards of Long Island, New York, contested the aerial spraying of dichlorodiphenyltrichloroethane (DDT).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] They compiled their evidence and shared it with Carson, who used it, their extensive contacts, and the trial transcripts as a primary input for *Silent Spring*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson wrote of the content as "a gold mine of information" and says, "I feel guilty about the mass of your material I have here" and makes multiple references to Pfeiffer and his correspondence.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] That spring, Carson wrote a letter, published in *The Washington Post*, that attributed the recent decline in bird populations—in her words, the "silencing of birds"—to pesticide overuse.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] That was also the year of the "Great Cranberry Scandal": the 1957, 1958, and 1959 crops of U.S. cranberries were found to contain high levels of the herbicide aminotriazole (which caused cancer in laboratory rats), and the sale of all cranberry products was halted.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson attended the subsequent FDA hearings on revising pesticide regulations; she came away discouraged by the aggressive tactics of the chemical industry representatives, which included expert testimony that was firmly contradicted by the bulk of the scientific literature she had been studying.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Research at the Library of Medicine of the National Institutes of Health brought Carson into contact with medical researchers investigating the gamut of cancer-causing chemicals.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Of particular significance was the work of National Cancer Institute researcher and environmental cancer section founding director Wilhelm Hueper, who classified many pesticides as carcinogens.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] By 1960, Carson had more than enough research material, and the writing was progressing rapidly.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In addition to the thorough literature search, she had investigated hundreds of individual incidents of pesticide exposure and the human sickness and ecological damage that resulted.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, in January, a duodenal ulcer followed by several infections kept her bedridden for weeks, greatly delaying the completion of *Silent Spring*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] As she was nearing full recovery in March (just as she was completing drafts of the two cancer chapters of her book), she discovered cysts in her left breast, one of which necessitated a mastectomy.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Though her doctor described the procedure as precautionary and recommended no further treatment, by December, Carson discovered that the tumor was malignant and the cancer had metastasized.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her research was also delayed by revision work for a new edition of *The Sea Around Us* and by a collaborative photo essay with Erich Hartmann.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Most of the research and writing was done by the fall of 1960, except for the discussion of recent research on biological pest controls and investigations of a handful of new pesticides.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, further health troubles slowed the final revisions in 1961 and early 1962.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] While writing the book, Carson chose to hide her illness so that the pesticide companies could not use it against her (she worried that if the companies knew, they would use it as ammunition to make her book look untrustworthy and biased).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Finding a title for the book proved difficult; "Silent Spring" was initially suggested as a title for the chapter on birds.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] By August 1961, Carson finally agreed to the suggestion of her literary agent Marie Rodell: *Silent Spring* would be a metaphorical title for the entire book, suggesting a bleak future for the whole natural world, rather than a single chapter title about the literal absence of birdsong.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] With Carson's approval, editor Paul Brooks at Houghton Mifflin arranged for illustrations by Louis and Lois Darling, who also designed the cover.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The final writing was the first chapter, *A Fable for Tomorrow*, which Carson intended as a gentle introduction to what might otherwise be a forbiddingly serious topic.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] By mid-1962, Brooks and Carson had essentially finished the editing and were laying the groundwork for promoting the book by sending the manuscript out to select individuals for final suggestions.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson's main argument is that pesticides have detrimental effects on the environment; they are more properly termed *biocides*, she argues, because their effects are rarely limited to the target pests.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] DDT is a prime example, but other synthetic pesticides come under scrutiny, many of which are subject to bioaccumulation.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson also accuses the chemical industry of intentionally spreading disinformation and public officials of accepting industry claims uncritically.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Most of the book is devoted to pesticides' effects on natural ecosystems.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, four chapters also detail cases of human pesticide poisoning, cancer, and other illnesses attributed to pesticides.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson predicted increased consequences in the future, especially as targeted pests develop pesticide resistance.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] At the same time, weakened ecosystems fall prey to unanticipated invasive species.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The book closes with a call for a biotic approach to pest control as an alternative to chemical pesticides.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Regarding DDT, Carson never called for an outright ban.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson further noted that "Malaria programmes are threatened by resistance among mosquitoes" and emphasized the advice given by the director of Holland's Plant Protection Service: "Practical advice should be 'Spray as little as you possibly can' rather than 'Spray to the limit of your capacity' ...
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson and the others involved with the publication of *Silent Spring* expected fierce criticism.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] They were particularly concerned about the possibility of being sued for libel.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson was also undergoing radiation therapy to combat her spreading cancer and expected to have little energy to devote to defending her work and responding to critics.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In preparation for the anticipated attacks, Carson and her agent attempted to amass as many prominent supporters as possible before the book's release.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Most of the book's scientific chapters were reviewed by scientists with relevant expertise, among whom Carson found strong support.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson attended the White House Conference on Conservation in May 1962; Houghton Mifflin distributed proof copies of *Silent Spring* to many of the delegates and promoted the upcoming *New Yorker* serialization.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Among many others, Carson also sent a proof copy to Supreme Court Associate Justice William O.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Douglas, a longtime environmental advocate who had argued against the court's rejection of the Long Island pesticide spraying case (and who had provided Carson with some of the material included in her chapter on herbicides).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Though *Silent Spring* had generated a relatively high level of interest based on pre-publication promotion, this became much more intense with the serialization in *The New Yorker*, which began on June 16, 1962, issue.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] This brought the book to the attention of the chemical industry and its lobbyists and a wide swath of the American populace.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The story of the birth defect-causing drug thalidomide broke just before the book's publication as well, inviting comparisons between Carson and Frances Oldham Kelsey, the Food and Drug Administration reviewer who had blocked the drug's sale in the United States.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Following the publication of *Silent Spring*, Carson as a woman in science faced personal attacks.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In the weeks leading up to the September 27, 1962, publication, there was strong opposition to *Silent Spring* from the chemical industry.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] DuPont (a high market-share manufacturer of DDT and 2,4-D) and Velsicol Chemical Corporation (exclusive manufacturer of chlordane and heptachlor) were among the first to respond.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] DuPont compiled an extensive report on the book's press coverage and estimated impact on public opinion.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Velsicol threatened legal action against Houghton Mifflin and *The New Yorker* and *Audubon* unless the planned *Silent Spring* features were canceled.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Chemical industry representatives and lobbyists also lodged a range of non-specific complaints, some anonymously.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Chemical companies and associated organizations produced a number of their own brochures and articles promoting and defending pesticide use.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, Carson's and the publishers' lawyers were confident in the vetting process *Silent Spring* had undergone.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The magazine and book publications proceeded as planned, as did the large Book-of-the-Month printing (which included a pamphlet endorsing the book by William O.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] American Cyanamid biochemist Robert White-Stevens and former Cyanamid chemist Thomas Jukes were among the most aggressive critics, especially of Carson's analysis of DDT.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] White-Stevens labeled her "...a fanatic defender of the cult of the balance of nature," while former U.S.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Secretary of Agriculture Ezra Taft Benson, in a letter to former President Dwight D.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Many critics repeatedly asserted that she was calling for the elimination of all pesticides.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] However, Carson had made it clear she was not advocating the banning or complete withdrawal of helpful pesticides but was instead encouraging responsible and carefully managed use with an awareness of the chemicals' impact on the entire ecosystem.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In fact, she concludes her section on DDT in *Silent Spring* not by urging a total ban but with advice for spraying as little as possible to limit the development of resistance.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The academic community, including prominent defenders such as H.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Muller, Loren Eiseley, Clarence Cottam, and Frank Egler, by and large, backed the book's scientific claims; public opinion soon turned Carson's way as well.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The chemical industry campaign backfired, as the controversy greatly increased public awareness of potential pesticide dangers, as well as *Silent Spring* book sales.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Pesticide use became a major public issue, especially after the *CBS Reports* TV special *The Silent Spring of Rachel Carson* that aired April 3, 1963.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The program included segments of Carson reading from *Silent Spring* and interviews with several other experts, mostly critics (including White-Stevens); according to biographer Linda Lear, "in juxtaposition to the wild-eyed, loud-voiced Dr.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Within a year or so of publication, the attacks on the book and Carson had largely lost momentum.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In one of her last public appearances, Carson testified before President John F.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The committee issued its report on May 15, 1963, largely backing Carson's scientific claims.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Following the report's release, she also testified before a United States Senate subcommittee to make policy recommendations.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Though Carson received hundreds of other speaking invitations, she could not accept the great majority of them.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her health was steadily declining as her cancer outpaced the radiation therapy, with only brief periods of remission.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She spoke as much as she was physically able, however, including a notable appearance on *The Today Show* and speeches at several dinners held in her honor.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In late 1963, she received a flurry of awards and honors: the Audubon Medal (from the National Audubon Society), the Cullum Geographical Medal (from the American Geographical Society), and induction into the American Academy of Arts and Letters.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Rachel Carson's writing style includes scientific report blended with imagery and narrative, aiming to emotionally appeal to her readers, in an effort to motivate environmental activism.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson utilizes grotesque imagery of the human body to reinforce the idea that humans are a part of nature .
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Another method she uses to reinforce human proximity to nature is creating sublimity within her writing .
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She uses natural imagery to demonstrate that humans are a small part of a much larger whole, deeming the environment as important as humans .
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] These stylistic choices emphasize the interconnectedness of humans and nature and influence the reader to develop a sense of empathy for the environment, resulting in feelings of responsibility to preserve and protect the natural world .
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Weakened from breast cancer and her treatment regimen, Carson became ill with a respiratory virus in January 1964.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her condition worsened, and in February, doctors found that she had severe anemia from her radiation treatments.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In March, they discovered that the cancer had reached her liver.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] She died of a heart attack on April 14, 1964, in her home in Silver Spring, Maryland.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her body was cremated, and some of her ashes were buried beside her mother at Parklawn Memorial Gardens in Rockville, Maryland.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The rest were scattered along the coast of Squirrel Island near Sheepscot River in Maine.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson bequeathed her manuscripts and papers to Yale University to take advantage of the new state-of-the-art preservations facilities of the Beinecke Rare Book & Manuscript Library.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her longtime agent and literary executor Marie Rodell spent nearly two years organizing and cataloging Carson's papers and correspondence, distributing all the letters to their senders so that only what each correspondent approved would be submitted to the archive.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 1965, Rodell arranged for the publication of an essay Carson had intended to expand into a book: *The Sense of Wonder*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In addition to the letters in *Always Rachel*, in 1998, a volume of Carson's previously unpublished work was published as *Lost Woods: The Discovered Writing of Rachel Carson*, edited by Linda Lear.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson's work had a powerful impact on the environmental movement.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] *Silent Spring*, in particular, was a rallying point for the fledgling social movement in the 1960s.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] According to environmental engineer and Carson scholar H.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Patricia Hynes, "*Silent Spring* altered the balance of power in the world.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] It was also influential on the rise of ecofeminism and on many feminist scientists.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] While there remains no evidence that Carson was openly a women's rights activist, her work and its subsequent criticisms have left an iconic legacy for the ecofeminist movement.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Others, such as Yaakov Garb, suggest that in addition to not being a women's rights activist, Carson also had no anti-capitalist agenda and that such attacks were unwarranted.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Additionally, the way photos of Carson were used to portray her are often questioned because of few representations of her engaging in work typical of a scientist, but instead of her leisure activities.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson's most direct legacy in the environmental movement was the campaign to ban DDT in the United States (and related efforts to ban or limit its use throughout the world).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Though environmental concerns about DDT had been considered by government agencies as early as Carson's testimony before the President's Science Advisory Committee, the 1967 formation of the Environmental Defense Fund was the first significant milestone in the campaign against DDT.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The organization brought lawsuits against the government to "establish a citizen's right to a clean environment," and the arguments employed against DDT largely mirrored Carson's.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] By 1972, the Environmental Defense Fund and other activist groups had succeeded in securing a phase-out of DDT use in the United States (except in emergency cases).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The creation of the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) by the Nixon Administration in 1970 addressed another concern that Carson had brought to light.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Until then, the same agency (the USDA) was responsible both for regulating pesticides and promoting the concerns of the agriculture industry; Carson saw this as a conflict of interest since the agency was not responsible for effects on wildlife or other environmental concerns beyond farm policy.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Fifteen years after its creation, one journalist described the EPA as "the extended shadow of *Silent Spring*." Much of the agency's early work, such as enforcing the 1972 Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act, was directly related to Carson's work.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In the 1980s, the policies of the Reagan Administration emphasized economic growth, rolling back many of the environmental policies adopted in response to Carson and her work.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Various groups ranging from government institutions to environmental and conservation organizations to scholarly societies have celebrated Carson's life and work since her death.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Perhaps most significantly, on June 9, 1980, Carson was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the highest civilian honor in the United States.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] A 17¢ Great Americans series postage stamp was issued in her honor the following year; several other countries have since issued Carson postage as well.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 1973, Carson was inducted into the National Women's Hall of Fame.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The University of California, Santa Cruz, named one of its colleges, formerly known as College Eight, Rachel Carson College in 2016.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Rachel Carson College is the first college at the university to bear a woman's name.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Munich's Rachel Carson Center for Environment and Society was founded in 2009.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson's birthplace and childhood home in Springdale, Pennsylvania, now known as the Rachel Carson Homestead, became a National Register of Historic Places site and the nonprofit Rachel Carson Homestead Association was created in 1975 to manage it.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Her home in Colesville, Maryland, where she wrote *Silent Spring*, was named a National Historic Landmark in 1991.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Near Pittsburgh, a 46.1 miles (74 km) hiking trail, the Rachel Carson Trail and maintained by the Rachel Carson Trails Conservancy, was dedicated to Carson in 1975.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] A Pittsburgh bridge was renamed in Carson's honor as the Rachel Carson Bridge.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection State Office Building in Harrisburg is named in her honor.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Two research vessels have sailed in the United States bearing the name R/V *Rachel Carson*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] One is on the west coast, owned by Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute (MBARI), and the other is on the east coast, operated by the University of Maryland Center for Environmental Science.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Another vessel of the name, now scrapped, was a former naval vessel obtained and converted by the United States EPA.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary also operates a mooring buoy maintenance vessel named the Rachel Carson.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The ceremonial auditorium on the third floor of EPA headquarters, the William Jefferson Clinton Federal Building, is named after Carson.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The Rachel Carson Room is close to the EPA Administrator's office.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] It has been the site of numerous important announcements, including the Clean Air Interstate Rule.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] A number of conservation areas have been named for Carson as well.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Between 1964 and 1990, 650 acres (263 ha) near Brookeville in Montgomery County, Maryland were acquired and set aside as the Rachel Carson Conservation Park, administered by the Maryland-National Capital Park and Planning Commission.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 1969, the Coastal Maine National Wildlife Refuge became the Rachel Carson National Wildlife Refuge; expansions will bring the size of the refuge to about 9,125 acres (3,693 ha).
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 1985, North Carolina renamed one of its estuarine reserves in honor of Carson, in Beaufort.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson is also a frequent namesake for prizes awarded by philanthropic, educational and scholarly institutions.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The Rachel Carson Prize, founded in Stavanger, Norway in 1991, is awarded to women who have made a contribution in the field of environmental protection.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The American Society for Environmental History has awarded the Rachel Carson Prize for Best Dissertation since 1993.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The Sierra Club and its foundation recognize donors who have provided for the club in their estate plans as the Rachel Carson Society.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The Rachel Carson Center for Environment and Society at Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München (Germany) awards post-doctoral fellowships in the area of the environment and society.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The *Rachel Carson* sculpture in Woods Hole, Massachusetts was unveiled on July 14, 2013.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Google created a Google Doodle for Carson's 107th birthday on May 27, 2014.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Carson was featured during the "HerStory" video tribute to notable women on U2's tour in 2017 for the 30th anniversary of *The Joshua Tree* during a performance of "Ultraviolet (Light My Way)" from the band's 1991 album *Achtung Baby*.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] In 2019, *Time* created 89 new covers to celebrate women of the year starting from 1920; it chose Carson for 1963.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The centennial of Carson's birth occurred in 2007.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] On Earth Day (April 22), *Courage for the Earth: Writers, Scientists, and Activists Celebrate the Life and Writing of Rachel Carson* released as "a centennial appreciation of Rachel Carson's brave life and transformative writing." It included 13 essays by environmental writers and scientists.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Cardin of Maryland had intended to submit a resolution celebrating Carson for her "legacy of scientific rigor coupled with poetic sensibility" on the 100th anniversary of her birth.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] The resolution was blocked by Republican Senator Tom Coburn of Oklahoma.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] On May 27, 2007, the Rachel Carson Homestead Association held a birthday party and sustainable feast at her birthplace and home in Springdale, Pennsylvania, and the first Rachel Carson Legacy Conference in Pittsburgh with E.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Both Rachel's Sustainable Feast and the conference continue as annual events.
[src:rachel-carson/rachel-carson-p01] Also in 2007, American author Ginger Wadsworth wrote a biography of Carson.
